00:03:03.040 --> 00:03:04.420
&gt;&gt; Andrew Witt: So we heard
a lot about structured data

00:03:04.420 --> 00:03:05.720
in the first half a day.

00:03:05.720 --> 00:03:08.000
I'm going to go in exactly the
opposite direction and talk

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:11.690
about a lot of unstructured
data and ways to deal with that,

00:03:11.690 --> 00:03:14.790
or semi-structured data
I guess I would say.

00:03:14.790 --> 00:03:18.830
So the expanded intellectual and
technical scope of architecture

00:03:18.830 --> 00:03:21.810
in the 20th and 21st Centuries
has drawn architects the use

00:03:21.810 --> 00:03:25.280
of automation to organize and
scale information and work.

00:03:25.280 --> 00:03:27.790
Automation includes both
commercial authoring software

00:03:27.790 --> 00:03:30.650
and the customized
scripts and softwares

00:03:30.650 --> 00:03:33.210
that designers, themselves,
create.

00:03:33.210 --> 00:03:36.480
These methods encapsulate or
black box domain knowledge

00:03:36.480 --> 00:03:38.680
to be applied automatically.

00:03:38.680 --> 00:03:40.540
And I showed this
image just to mention

00:03:40.540 --> 00:03:43.680
like in a previous life
Dennis and I worked together

00:03:43.680 --> 00:03:46.960
at Deerey Technologies
and I curated this sort

00:03:46.960 --> 00:03:50.470
of like portion of this massive
retrospective of the provenance

00:03:50.470 --> 00:03:52.960
of Frank Deerey's use of
technology, and so a lot

00:03:52.960 --> 00:03:55.270
of my perspective is
shaped by like digging

00:03:55.270 --> 00:03:56.570
through those archives
and trying

00:03:56.570 --> 00:03:59.980
to reassemble what actually
went on when those things were,

00:03:59.980 --> 00:04:02.680
when those buildings
were being put together.

00:04:02.680 --> 00:04:07.150
So scripting has significantly
impacted how design is developed

00:04:07.150 --> 00:04:10.590
and, thus, how historians must
understand digital documents.

00:04:10.590 --> 00:04:13.460
So here I'm going to propose
three implications of that.

00:04:13.460 --> 00:04:16.470
First, source code as
a historical document.

00:04:16.470 --> 00:04:19.710
Second, digital forensics,
and I realized actually

00:04:19.710 --> 00:04:21.570
after the first session that
I'm using this term forensics

00:04:21.570 --> 00:04:26.000
in a slightly different way
than the sort of technical term

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:28.230
of art sense, but
we'll get into that.

00:04:28.230 --> 00:04:31.510
And, third, AI archival agents.

00:04:31.510 --> 00:04:34.100
Ultimately the possibility is
that historians, themselves,

00:04:34.100 --> 00:04:37.290
might script their own tools
to understand these documents

00:04:37.290 --> 00:04:40.420
and at the frontiers of this
possibility are the applications

00:04:40.420 --> 00:04:43.560
of things like sentiment
analysis, machine vision,

00:04:43.560 --> 00:04:48.540
artificial intelligence to crawl
archives, yes, to crawl archives

00:04:48.540 --> 00:04:52.340
and sort of make sense
of them at a large scale.

00:04:52.340 --> 00:04:54.660
So this is a video
of a textual analysis

00:04:54.660 --> 00:04:57.640
of important theoretical text

00:04:57.640 --> 00:04:59.340
from the '60s called
the pattern language.

00:04:59.340 --> 00:05:01.610
It applies sentiment
analysis ideas

00:05:01.610 --> 00:05:04.820
to theoretical architectural
text and then compares them

00:05:04.820 --> 00:05:07.350
to understand who is being
sort of the most polemic,

00:05:07.350 --> 00:05:12.550
the most sort of like unbiased,
and the most sort of hyperbolic.

00:05:13.660 --> 00:05:17.200
So computational processes
in design have given rise

00:05:17.200 --> 00:05:19.020
to new kinds of collateral
documents,

00:05:19.020 --> 00:05:21.560
and one potentially very
rich new archive, obviously,

00:05:21.560 --> 00:05:23.840
these scripts and
code bases themselves

00:05:23.840 --> 00:05:26.080
for the applications
developed specifically

00:05:26.080 --> 00:05:27.950
for design projects.

00:05:27.950 --> 00:05:30.290
The language in which code
is written, the organization

00:05:30.290 --> 00:05:34.080
of its components, the subject
domains of the external modules

00:05:34.080 --> 00:05:36.890
that it draws on, all of these
reveal certain proclivities

00:05:36.890 --> 00:05:40.710
in the way that designers choose
to organize technical knowledge.

00:05:40.710 --> 00:05:42.690
And it suggests how
designers, themselves,

00:05:42.690 --> 00:05:45.540
might feel about how
architectural practice might

00:05:45.540 --> 00:05:46.950
evolve in the future.

00:05:46.950 --> 00:05:49.010
So each of them are sort of
like putting a stake in the sand

00:05:49.010 --> 00:05:51.480
about how they think the
discipline should evolve.

00:05:51.480 --> 00:05:54.180
So let's contrast two projects
that are actually drawn

00:05:54.180 --> 00:05:56.190
from the CCA's digital
archive --

00:05:56.190 --> 00:05:57.990
Mark Goldfarb's [assumed
spelling] hypo surface

00:05:57.990 --> 00:06:01.810
and Chuck Hoberman's iris dome.

00:06:01.810 --> 00:06:04.250
So we'll begin with
the iris dome.

00:06:04.250 --> 00:06:08.520
So both of these projects are
large geometrically complex

00:06:08.520 --> 00:06:10.320
kinematic installations

00:06:10.320 --> 00:06:12.920
with very sophisticated
mechanical systems.

00:06:12.920 --> 00:06:16.590
Both are composed of hundreds
of custom moving parts

00:06:16.590 --> 00:06:17.890
and they both relied

00:06:17.890 --> 00:06:22.030
on extensive scripted automation
directed by the designer.

00:06:22.030 --> 00:06:24.980
But the distinction
between the use of scripting

00:06:24.980 --> 00:06:27.130
and automation is I
think very revealing,

00:06:27.130 --> 00:06:28.790
so we'll begin with Hoberman.

00:06:28.790 --> 00:06:30.090
So Hoberman's archive preserves

00:06:30.090 --> 00:06:33.810
about 74 distinct scripts
developed in the lisp language

00:06:33.810 --> 00:06:36.640
of AutoCAD, so any
of you who have been

00:06:36.640 --> 00:06:39.300
around for a little while
that probably takes you back.

00:06:39.300 --> 00:06:40.600
These scripts were
used to layout

00:06:40.600 --> 00:06:41.900
and draw the mechanical
components

00:06:41.900 --> 00:06:43.900
of his complex assemblies
and, thus,

00:06:43.900 --> 00:06:45.850
were reused on multiple
projects.

00:06:45.850 --> 00:06:49.020
It became a sort of
repository for knowledge reuse.

00:06:49.020 --> 00:06:50.320
It became a way to automate

00:06:50.320 --> 00:06:53.590
and parametrically adapt
certain aspects of the design.

00:06:53.590 --> 00:06:56.230
And on the dome project
Hoberman had

00:06:56.230 --> 00:06:58.840
about 12 different specific
scripts for that project

00:06:58.840 --> 00:07:00.520
and about 52 drawing files.

00:07:00.520 --> 00:07:03.290
So as a general rule maybe like
20% of the design intelligence

00:07:03.290 --> 00:07:07.620
of the project was
embedded in the source code.

00:07:07.620 --> 00:07:11.980
So Hoberman developed
these tools as pragmatic,

00:07:11.980 --> 00:07:14.120
on a pragmatic and
on demand basis

00:07:14.120 --> 00:07:16.160
to address very specific
problems, so it's really obvious

00:07:16.160 --> 00:07:17.530
when you're reading
through these

00:07:17.530 --> 00:07:18.860
that he wrote them himself,

00:07:18.860 --> 00:07:20.540
he didn't really
document them extensively,

00:07:20.540 --> 00:07:21.840
if you know anything

00:07:21.840 --> 00:07:23.670
about source code there were
very, very few comments.

00:07:23.670 --> 00:07:26.920
And the way in which they're
written is kind of like it's raw

00:07:26.920 --> 00:07:29.190
in a way, but it's
also very adaptable.

00:07:29.190 --> 00:07:30.490
They're written in a code style

00:07:30.490 --> 00:07:33.510
which suggests a very
specific single author and user

00:07:33.510 --> 00:07:37.780
and very sort of like targeted
and tactical applications.

00:07:37.780 --> 00:07:40.710
So Mark Goldfarb's approach

00:07:40.710 --> 00:07:43.260
to hypo surface was
quite different.

00:07:43.260 --> 00:07:45.400
It was a single and
unique project,

00:07:45.400 --> 00:07:47.320
a significant monumental
project,

00:07:47.320 --> 00:07:48.620
but a single project nonetheless

00:07:48.620 --> 00:07:51.750
and there was no
knowledge with use per se.

00:07:51.750 --> 00:07:53.910
Instead there was
a need through code

00:07:53.910 --> 00:07:57.330
to manage a complex
collaboration structure.

00:07:57.330 --> 00:07:59.370
So the project demanded
support from a range

00:07:59.370 --> 00:08:01.910
of unusual consultants,
people like mathematicians,

00:08:01.910 --> 00:08:05.500
megatronics experts, pneumatics
engineers, rubber researchers.

00:08:05.500 --> 00:08:07.860
So architects are no
strangers to collaboration,

00:08:07.860 --> 00:08:11.040
but these particular domains
were quite I would say foreign

00:08:11.040 --> 00:08:13.040
to typical architecture
practice.

00:08:13.040 --> 00:08:15.070
So the single software
application became one

00:08:15.070 --> 00:08:17.450
of the templates for managing
that collaborative knowledge.

00:08:17.450 --> 00:08:20.870
So, yes, there wasn't
knowledge use per se,

00:08:20.870 --> 00:08:24.240
and so there was a need
to manage these domains.

00:08:24.240 --> 00:08:25.940
So the software components
were developed

00:08:25.940 --> 00:08:28.670
by Goldfarb's team members,

00:08:28.670 --> 00:08:30.520
primarily Zaviae Rubitai
[assumed spelling],

00:08:30.520 --> 00:08:32.950
who is sort of like
listed in this organogram.

00:08:32.950 --> 00:08:36.210
And instead of a flat list of
the spoke scripts as you have

00:08:36.210 --> 00:08:38.500
in Hoberman's case the hypo
service team hierarchically

00:08:38.500 --> 00:08:42.500
combined componentized libraries
into more extensive packages

00:08:42.500 --> 00:08:43.850
and a single coordinated
software.

00:08:43.850 --> 00:08:46.080
So you have a more
hierarchical organization,

00:08:46.080 --> 00:08:49.690
which essentially mirrors
the project team structure.

00:08:49.690 --> 00:08:54.290
So mathematical,
mechanical, electrical control

00:08:54.290 --> 00:08:57.200
and design parameters all
coexisted in the software.

00:08:57.200 --> 00:09:00.040
It wasn't intended actually
to automate the design

00:09:00.040 --> 00:09:02.980
of the hypo surface,
as in Hoberman's case,

00:09:02.980 --> 00:09:04.830
but instead to automate
its control

00:09:04.830 --> 00:09:06.130
and in particular the motion

00:09:06.130 --> 00:09:07.760
of the hundreds of
linear actuators.

00:09:07.760 --> 00:09:09.780
So here in this exploded
assay you can see

00:09:09.780 --> 00:09:12.390
where those linear
actuators fall.

00:09:12.390 --> 00:09:13.690
And I think it's kind

00:09:13.690 --> 00:09:14.990
of interesting is you
have the layers of sort

00:09:14.990 --> 00:09:16.290
of like electrical control,

00:09:16.290 --> 00:09:18.920
sort of like this very
specific this spoke rubber,

00:09:18.920 --> 00:09:21.740
the actuators themselves,
and the architecture kind

00:09:21.740 --> 00:09:23.050
of like mirrors in a
certain way the script

00:09:23.050 --> 00:09:24.350
organization actually.

00:09:24.350 --> 00:09:32.090
Yes, so Hoberman and Golfarb's
approaches illustrate two

00:09:32.090 --> 00:09:33.960
architype of different
approaches to code.

00:09:33.960 --> 00:09:36.930
The artisan computational
designer, maybe in the case

00:09:36.930 --> 00:09:38.770
of Hoberman, on the one hand

00:09:38.770 --> 00:09:41.380
and the organization
builder on the other.

00:09:41.380 --> 00:09:43.980
One effectively synthesizes
knowledge,

00:09:43.980 --> 00:09:46.580
synthesizes that knowledge him
or herself, so Hoberman was sort

00:09:46.580 --> 00:09:49.420
of like a sculptor, an
architect and an engineer.

00:09:49.420 --> 00:09:53.190
The other is a means, the
other uses code as a means

00:09:53.190 --> 00:09:54.490
of knowledge synthesis.

00:09:54.490 --> 00:09:56.500
So both are kind of
forerunners in a certain way

00:09:56.500 --> 00:10:00.020
of approaches that we see today.

00:10:00.020 --> 00:10:03.480
Now computers are not
only geometry producers,

00:10:03.480 --> 00:10:05.680
but they're also
recorders, obviously.

00:10:05.680 --> 00:10:07.560
So a digitally conceived
drawing is, in fact,

00:10:07.560 --> 00:10:10.430
just an automatic
log of transactions.

00:10:10.430 --> 00:10:14.280
And the operations recorded
therein are sometimes atomically

00:10:14.280 --> 00:10:16.660
stamped with things
like time, location,

00:10:16.660 --> 00:10:19.010
and authorship information.

00:10:19.010 --> 00:10:21.760
The automatic nature of digital
recording can actually be a tool

00:10:21.760 --> 00:10:25.280
for very interesting forensic
reconstruction processes.

00:10:25.280 --> 00:10:28.740
So a curious quality of these
particular kinds of sequences

00:10:28.740 --> 00:10:32.050
of operation is that they record
chronologically not only human

00:10:32.050 --> 00:10:33.910
authorship, but also
the sequence

00:10:33.910 --> 00:10:36.560
of certain algorithmic
processes.

00:10:36.560 --> 00:10:39.390
So I should mention
there's some great work here

00:10:39.390 --> 00:10:43.020
from Jona Rhys Meyers and
Renbe [assumed spelling],

00:10:43.020 --> 00:10:46.620
who were involved
with this project.

00:10:46.620 --> 00:10:48.870
So different software
generates the same dome

00:10:48.870 --> 00:10:51.080
in different ways
leading to distinct

00:10:51.080 --> 00:10:53.520
and characteristic
operational footprints.

00:10:53.520 --> 00:10:56.520
For example, this diagram
compares a different programs

00:10:56.520 --> 00:11:00.390
log operationally sequences
in slightly different ways.

00:11:00.390 --> 00:11:02.530
&gt;&gt; Five minutes, so.

00:11:02.530 --> 00:11:03.970
&gt;&gt; Andrew Witt: Really, okay.

00:11:03.970 --> 00:11:06.570
My stopwatch says
differently, but maybe.

00:11:06.570 --> 00:11:08.370
Thanks to the journaled
and sequential nature

00:11:08.370 --> 00:11:11.090
of digital design files we
can reconstruct the chronology

00:11:11.090 --> 00:11:12.580
of their creation.

00:11:12.580 --> 00:11:15.950
So with certain formats, I mean
it's very format particular,

00:11:15.950 --> 00:11:17.480
but this allows us to see step

00:11:17.480 --> 00:11:20.800
by step how a designer
modeled the particular form.

00:11:20.800 --> 00:11:24.550
It can even allow us to see
gaps, erasures and hesitations.

00:11:24.550 --> 00:11:27.820
So here we see the timeline
of a particular Revit file

00:11:27.820 --> 00:11:30.360
and the sort of like
chronological deconstruction

00:11:30.360 --> 00:11:31.660
of that file.

00:11:31.660 --> 00:11:33.860
So at the far right you see a
sort of like linear sequence

00:11:33.860 --> 00:11:37.280
of how the designer
actually modeled that file.

00:11:37.280 --> 00:11:39.460
So we can visualize
these sequences

00:11:39.460 --> 00:11:43.410
as three dimensional exploitive
econometrics revealing a kind

00:11:43.410 --> 00:11:44.710
of digital column SaaS

00:11:44.710 --> 00:11:47.070
and literally see the
design process unfold.

00:11:47.070 --> 00:11:51.660
So this is a matrix of a series
of these kind of exploited axos,

00:11:51.660 --> 00:11:54.020
and it's very, you know, it's
revealing in certain cases

00:11:54.020 --> 00:11:55.750
because you begin to understand,
okay, what are the problems

00:11:55.750 --> 00:11:57.500
that the architect sort of
like really labored over,

00:11:57.500 --> 00:11:59.590
what are the problems which
were really sort of like done

00:11:59.590 --> 00:12:01.230
as a matter of course,
and we can begin

00:12:01.230 --> 00:12:07.770
to interpret priorities in
these sort of expanded drawings.

00:12:07.770 --> 00:12:12.440
So, yes, it's possible to track,
journal and visualize authorship

00:12:12.440 --> 00:12:16.360
in real time, just as -- yes,
so it's possible to do this

00:12:16.360 --> 00:12:17.660
in real-time, as well.

00:12:17.660 --> 00:12:21.010
So just as our eyes track
irregular cicada patterns,

00:12:21.010 --> 00:12:24.960
designers in the sort of
irregular way also rotate,

00:12:24.960 --> 00:12:27.620
flip and work with their models.

00:12:27.620 --> 00:12:30.310
I'm not sure how this line
drawing is coming through,

00:12:30.310 --> 00:12:33.740
but essentially this is
a process of modeling

00:12:33.740 --> 00:12:36.550
which has tracked the motions
of the designer, themselves.

00:12:36.550 --> 00:12:39.130
So you can see how the
designer manipulates the models.

00:12:39.130 --> 00:12:42.520
