00:32:11.210 --> 00:32:12.810
&gt;&gt; Matthew Allen: So what
I thought I could bring

00:32:12.810 --> 00:32:16.420
to this particular panel
is a discussion of some

00:32:16.420 --> 00:32:17.720
of the more normal ways

00:32:17.720 --> 00:32:22.200
that a architectural historian
might use the digital archive.

00:32:22.200 --> 00:32:23.500
[laughter] So the
projects I'll talk

00:32:23.500 --> 00:32:26.520
about aren't using cutting edge
methods and they weren't carried

00:32:26.520 --> 00:32:28.350
out with a lot of resources.

00:32:28.350 --> 00:32:32.430
I wanted to highlight that
the typical conditions

00:32:32.430 --> 00:32:33.920
under which an architectural --

00:32:33.920 --> 00:32:35.290
&gt;&gt; There will be a rebuttal.

00:32:35.290 --> 00:32:37.360
[laughter]

00:32:37.360 --> 00:32:40.330
&gt;&gt; Matthew Allen: Especially
I'm thinking in particular

00:32:40.330 --> 00:32:42.570
of historians approaching
a topic

00:32:42.570 --> 00:32:45.620
that they aren't even sure
they want to commit to sort

00:32:45.620 --> 00:32:49.110
of working on and what
they maybe might look

00:32:49.110 --> 00:32:50.410
for in an archive.

00:32:50.410 --> 00:32:55.010
So I'll discuss three
projects that have led so far

00:32:55.010 --> 00:32:58.570
to three small exhibitions.

00:32:58.570 --> 00:33:01.820
The starting point for the first
project was Greg Lynn's [assumed

00:33:01.820 --> 00:33:04.780
spelling] observation about how
software is sometimes visible

00:33:04.780 --> 00:33:07.200
in images of architectural
design.

00:33:07.200 --> 00:33:11.060
In this case different
software allows users

00:33:11.060 --> 00:33:14.680
to create different
types of lines or curves.

00:33:14.680 --> 00:33:19.790
My question was given a bunch
of images of design projects

00:33:19.790 --> 00:33:23.000
from a certain period
can we infer

00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:24.860
which software was
used to make them?

00:33:24.860 --> 00:33:27.240
Beyond this can we start
to analyze the feedback

00:33:27.240 --> 00:33:30.200
between software and ways of
thinking about architecture?

00:33:30.200 --> 00:33:35.440
From the time I spent in
the Exhibition Department

00:33:35.440 --> 00:33:37.750
at the Harvard Graduate
School of Design I knew

00:33:37.750 --> 00:33:40.220
that they had a set of student
projects that they collected

00:33:40.220 --> 00:33:42.460
at the end of every semester.

00:33:42.460 --> 00:33:45.820
Because these were just quick
student projects the images were

00:33:45.820 --> 00:33:47.230
not very polished.

00:33:47.230 --> 00:33:49.950
The evidence of the software
hadn't been scrubbed away,

00:33:49.950 --> 00:33:51.550
so to speak.

00:33:51.550 --> 00:33:54.380
This collection was not
really archived, per se.

00:33:54.380 --> 00:33:59.080
The computing services team
had done some work putting the

00:33:59.080 --> 00:34:01.590
collection in order,
but what I had to work

00:34:01.590 --> 00:34:05.370
with was essentially a
pile of about 28,000 JPEGs

00:34:05.370 --> 00:34:10.590
from about 5,000 projects and
an Excel file with all sorts

00:34:10.590 --> 00:34:12.950
of different metadata.

00:34:12.950 --> 00:34:16.850
So knowing that the files were
there I suggested an exhibition

00:34:16.850 --> 00:34:18.760
to the school and
they graciously agreed

00:34:18.760 --> 00:34:21.470
to give me a wall
in the library.

00:34:21.470 --> 00:34:25.880
I also proposed linking the
show to research I was doing

00:34:25.880 --> 00:34:28.810
on older software, so the
show became a dual exhibition

00:34:28.810 --> 00:34:34.370
on software in the '60s and '70s
and software in the recent past.

00:34:34.370 --> 00:34:36.280
Finally, part of the project was

00:34:36.280 --> 00:34:39.250
to more properly archive the
student work so the idea was

00:34:39.250 --> 00:34:42.320
to sort of usher the
work into the library,

00:34:42.320 --> 00:34:45.810
both symbolically
and physically.

00:34:45.810 --> 00:34:47.110
Because I had a hard drive

00:34:47.110 --> 00:34:50.500
with all the files access was
not particularly difficult.

00:34:50.500 --> 00:34:53.550
I made a copy of the files,
renamed them and looked

00:34:53.550 --> 00:34:56.010
at them all with a few
different image viewers.

00:34:56.010 --> 00:34:59.460
I tagged them, sorted
them, rearranged them based

00:34:59.460 --> 00:35:02.740
on visual conventions that I
thought that I was interested in

00:35:02.740 --> 00:35:07.410
and how I might be able
to use them in the show.

00:35:07.410 --> 00:35:09.820
Part of the show was a
wash of all of the images,

00:35:09.820 --> 00:35:12.990
so I wrote a script to shrink
them and combine them together

00:35:12.990 --> 00:35:17.590
and lay them out in a series
of PDF files for printing.

00:35:17.590 --> 00:35:19.870
Another section had the
names of all the students --

00:35:19.870 --> 00:35:23.920
oh, here's a -- so
this is the wall.

00:35:23.920 --> 00:35:26.820
Another section had the names
of all the students involved

00:35:26.820 --> 00:35:32.700
so I copied and pasted from
Excel to InDesign for that.

00:35:32.700 --> 00:35:35.720
[laughter] Finally, there was a
slide show that pulled out some

00:35:35.720 --> 00:35:38.600
of the images and correlated
them with little bits of text

00:35:38.600 --> 00:35:45.670
that sort of analyzed the
visual conventions involved,

00:35:45.670 --> 00:35:49.840
so this slide show was
playing in the library.

00:35:49.840 --> 00:35:53.230
This is what the exhibition
looked like in the end.

00:35:53.230 --> 00:35:55.800
There was also a little
wall with screenshots

00:35:55.800 --> 00:35:58.380
of current projects that
I solicited from students

00:35:58.380 --> 00:36:00.360
at the school, sort
of a live feed

00:36:00.360 --> 00:36:03.320
of what was happening
upstairs in the school.

00:36:03.320 --> 00:36:05.950
I'll also note that my ambition
has been to put this research

00:36:05.950 --> 00:36:09.180
into a sort of field guide
of the visual conventions

00:36:09.180 --> 00:36:11.910
of architectural software
during this period,

00:36:11.910 --> 00:36:14.190
so I was somewhat
rigorous about sort

00:36:14.190 --> 00:36:17.100
of what I was looking
for in these files.

00:36:17.100 --> 00:36:21.400
All right, one lesson
from this project begins

00:36:21.400 --> 00:36:22.970
with the observation
that it only worked

00:36:22.970 --> 00:36:26.020
because I had unusually
direct access to the files.

00:36:26.020 --> 00:36:27.900
I could flip through thousands

00:36:27.900 --> 00:36:30.280
of JPEG files, sort
them, tag them.

00:36:30.280 --> 00:36:35.660
It's hard to imagine doing this
without direct access like that.

00:36:35.660 --> 00:36:38.950
This was similar to digging

00:36:38.950 --> 00:36:42.810
through physical
archives in some ways.

00:36:42.810 --> 00:36:47.030
In both cases we're
confronted with a pile of stuff

00:36:47.030 --> 00:36:50.130
which we can pull things
out from and put it back

00:36:50.130 --> 00:36:53.590
as we want very quickly with
digital files creating this sort

00:36:53.590 --> 00:36:55.830
of hands-on feeling

00:36:55.830 --> 00:36:59.420
of manipulation is
essential I think.

00:36:59.420 --> 00:37:02.010
I'd like to imagine that there's
no good reason it can't be made

00:37:02.010 --> 00:37:04.360
possible to check-out
an entire archive

00:37:04.360 --> 00:37:07.330
on an external hard
drive, for example.

00:37:07.330 --> 00:37:10.410
My point here is that
historians are usually operating

00:37:10.410 --> 00:37:14.630
under a severe time crunch,
especially when deciding whether

00:37:14.630 --> 00:37:18.380
to work on a project or not,
and if it appears difficult

00:37:18.380 --> 00:37:20.650
to get ahold of the files
they may choose not to take

00:37:20.650 --> 00:37:22.980
on the project at all, right?

00:37:22.980 --> 00:37:26.610
Okay, the second project
I'll talk about begins also

00:37:26.610 --> 00:37:31.000
with a heap of files, but it
was a more heterogeneous heap.

