00:38:47.020 --> 00:38:50.140
for an exhibition the architect
had some incentive to help,

00:38:50.140 --> 00:38:53.270
of course, so I sat down
with him and went through all

00:38:53.270 --> 00:38:56.810
of the files comparing
differences and trying to figure

00:38:56.810 --> 00:39:01.310
out how sort of what changed
between the versions and why.

00:39:01.310 --> 00:39:04.260
So the process involved
a lot of comparison

00:39:04.260 --> 00:39:07.280
of different types of files.

00:39:07.280 --> 00:39:10.220
We also in the process
made a bunch of diagrams.

00:39:10.220 --> 00:39:13.390
In fact, it was through this
process of drawing diagrams

00:39:13.390 --> 00:39:17.380
that a lot of the important
points came out and sort

00:39:17.380 --> 00:39:19.130
of jogged their memory.

00:39:19.130 --> 00:39:22.360
One of the coolest things
we found was this little

00:39:22.360 --> 00:39:25.960
geometrical sketch, off to
the side, of one of the files,

00:39:25.960 --> 00:39:29.070
which was later sort of moved
into the middle of the building

00:39:29.070 --> 00:39:32.510
and became the sort of focal
point of the whole project

00:39:32.510 --> 00:39:35.420
as you can see on the left.

00:39:35.420 --> 00:39:39.630
All right, so it's clear

00:39:39.630 --> 00:39:42.510
that insider knowledge
was key to the exhibition.

00:39:42.510 --> 00:39:44.360
Without the architect
to carefully think

00:39:44.360 --> 00:39:48.010
through the design process,
pulling out important moments

00:39:48.010 --> 00:39:51.400
from the files would have been
a much more difficult task.

00:39:51.400 --> 00:39:53.460
One useful archival
practice then,

00:39:53.460 --> 00:39:57.300
and this was mentioned earlier
and especially for small firms,

00:39:57.300 --> 00:40:00.570
would be to ask designers
to spend some time

00:40:00.570 --> 00:40:05.160
after a project is over simply
copying and pasting sort

00:40:05.160 --> 00:40:09.130
of some key files to a separate
folder that could serve as sort

00:40:09.130 --> 00:40:12.240
of reference points later
on if you wanted to sort

00:40:12.240 --> 00:40:13.750
of reconstruct the
design process.

00:40:13.750 --> 00:40:18.300
All right, going through these
files I found a collection

00:40:18.300 --> 00:40:22.320
of documents, I found that
a collection of documents

00:40:22.320 --> 00:40:25.480
in their original order
provided some valuable clues

00:40:25.480 --> 00:40:26.780
for the historian.

00:40:26.780 --> 00:40:28.860
A folder structure
can tell you a lot.

00:40:28.860 --> 00:40:32.730
File adjacencies are sometimes
meaningful to make sense

00:40:32.730 --> 00:40:34.970
of a workflow, having
access to files

00:40:34.970 --> 00:40:38.150
in their original structure
is sometimes crucial.

00:40:38.150 --> 00:40:43.200
Things like scripts or reference
images, next to original models

00:40:43.200 --> 00:40:46.720
or drawings, you know, can
make all the difference

00:40:46.720 --> 00:40:48.180
in interpreting it.

00:40:48.180 --> 00:40:52.030
In contemporary modeling
practices the best way to ensure

00:40:52.030 --> 00:40:56.050
that a model would even
open correctly would be

00:40:56.050 --> 00:40:59.440
to have a sort of snapshot of
the whole computer it seems like

00:40:59.440 --> 00:41:02.700
and actually absent that
it's hard to guarantee

00:41:02.700 --> 00:41:05.610
that some things would
even work at all, right?

00:41:06.630 --> 00:41:10.880
I think ultimately that the
way to think about design needs

00:41:10.880 --> 00:41:14.230
to change drastically as we
think about digital archives.

00:41:14.230 --> 00:41:17.440
Sometimes I personally
lapse into imagining

00:41:17.440 --> 00:41:19.980
that design is something an
architect does with pencil

00:41:19.980 --> 00:41:23.100
and paper, and then I go to
look for sketches and drawings

00:41:23.100 --> 00:41:25.440
for evidence of design
decisions.

00:41:25.440 --> 00:41:28.370
But it's clear that with digital
design an architect is usually

00:41:28.370 --> 00:41:30.980
looking over someone else's
shoulder as they're zooming in

00:41:30.980 --> 00:41:33.820
and out, turning layers on
and off, and rotating things

00:41:33.820 --> 00:41:35.900
to get just the right view.

00:41:35.900 --> 00:41:38.810
The important thing is not
only to look at the right file,

00:41:38.810 --> 00:41:40.610
but to have the right
viewpoint within the file,

00:41:40.610 --> 00:41:43.100
the right combination
of layers and so on.

00:41:43.100 --> 00:41:46.630
So digital files have a much
greater depth and complexity

00:41:46.630 --> 00:41:49.060
than drawings on paper,
I mean we all know this.

00:41:49.060 --> 00:41:52.160
But luckily historians can
approach archives in new ways.

00:41:52.160 --> 00:41:54.960
We don't have to be
respectful of digital files

00:41:54.960 --> 00:41:58.540
in the same way we are
careful about drawings.

00:41:58.540 --> 00:42:00.940
We can make a copy of everything
and move things around,

00:42:00.940 --> 00:42:04.660
cut out pieces, save as
new files, delete things,

00:42:04.660 --> 00:42:07.260
create our own folder
structure and so on.

00:42:07.260 --> 00:42:12.310
The more this can be
enabled I think the better.

00:42:12.310 --> 00:42:14.380
All right, so the third project

00:42:14.380 --> 00:42:17.540
that I'll just very briefly
discuss builds on the second.

00:42:17.540 --> 00:42:21.130
As an architecture student I
came to appreciate the impact

00:42:21.130 --> 00:42:25.790
of software limitations
and bugs on design.

00:42:25.790 --> 00:42:27.230
If you know that a
program will crash

00:42:27.230 --> 00:42:30.400
after you have let's say
10,000 of something you'll try

00:42:30.400 --> 00:42:33.180
to design with only 9,000
of them, and then once

00:42:33.180 --> 00:42:35.110
that bug is fixed
you'll go crazy and make

00:42:35.110 --> 00:42:38.610
like 100,000 of them, right?

00:42:38.610 --> 00:42:42.630
I know that 10 years ago
students were eagerly installing

00:42:42.630 --> 00:42:44.980
beta versions of software
as soon as it came

00:42:44.980 --> 00:42:48.570
out to use the latest features.

00:42:48.570 --> 00:42:51.670
So this final project was an
exploration of the relationship

00:42:51.670 --> 00:42:54.550
between the evolution of
software and the evolution

00:42:54.550 --> 00:42:58.370
of architectural culture
and ultimately the evolution

00:42:58.370 --> 00:43:00.860
of architecture,
itself, let's say.

00:43:00.860 --> 00:43:03.090
I didn't begin with a
traditional archive,

00:43:03.090 --> 00:43:05.900
but three different
sources of information.

00:43:05.900 --> 00:43:08.850
The first was the change
log of Rhinoceros 3D,

00:43:08.850 --> 00:43:12.370
a popular digital
modeling package.

00:43:12.370 --> 00:43:15.620
I knew the change log
was available in pieces,

00:43:15.620 --> 00:43:19.260
but I wasn't able to get it
directly from McNeel so I ended

00:43:19.260 --> 00:43:24.140
up pulling it piece by piece
from archive.org actually.

00:43:24.140 --> 00:43:28.260
The second source was text
and images from forums

00:43:28.260 --> 00:43:32.210
that showed bugs that
architects encountered in Rhino.

00:43:32.210 --> 00:43:36.110
And for the third I put a call
out to friends and students

00:43:36.110 --> 00:43:40.320
for anecdotes about what they
thought was the most important

00:43:40.320 --> 00:43:42.370
command in Rhino.

00:43:42.370 --> 00:43:44.940
So the idea of the show
was to fill-up a wall

00:43:44.940 --> 00:43:48.520
with the change logging and
to correlate the anecdotes

00:43:48.520 --> 00:43:50.590
and the images with it.

00:43:50.590 --> 00:43:55.710
So this is sort of
what it looked like.

00:43:55.710 --> 00:43:58.970
So again it was to, so at
certain points you could see

00:43:58.970 --> 00:44:02.310
in the change log that a new
command would be added to Rhino

00:44:02.310 --> 00:44:05.270
and then there would be
anecdotes about like how

00:44:05.270 --> 00:44:09.910
that particular command related
to architectural design, right?

00:44:09.910 --> 00:44:13.480
So it made a good
conversation piece definitely.

00:44:13.480 --> 00:44:17.380
Let's see, where are we -- and
it may have gotten some people

00:44:17.380 --> 00:44:19.380
to think about the
link between the sort

00:44:19.380 --> 00:44:22.730
of behind the scenes
practices of software design

00:44:22.730 --> 00:44:25.450
and our own design work.

00:44:25.450 --> 00:44:29.220
I wanted to show this project
here to emphasize the relevance

00:44:29.220 --> 00:44:34.460
of all this seemingly peripheral
stuff to architectural projects.

00:44:34.460 --> 00:44:38.000
If as a historian you're not
focusing on finished buildings,

00:44:38.000 --> 00:44:39.300
a lot of the things

00:44:39.300 --> 00:44:42.140
in traditional archives
simply don't get to the point.

00:44:42.140 --> 00:44:45.270
For this show I didn't want
drawings or renderings,

00:44:45.270 --> 00:44:47.870
but screenshots and forum posts.

00:44:47.870 --> 00:44:49.670
If I'm trying to
focus on some aspect

00:44:49.670 --> 00:44:53.150
of architectural culture
archival work becomes something

00:44:53.150 --> 00:44:55.240
like anthropological fieldwork.

00:44:55.240 --> 00:44:58.810
Part of the job is to scout
out possible archives.

00:44:58.810 --> 00:45:00.950
So in this case if I care
about the impact of software

00:45:00.950 --> 00:45:04.230
in architecture it makes me
wonder if we should be thinking

00:45:04.230 --> 00:45:06.750
of archiving not only
old versions of software,

00:45:06.750 --> 00:45:08.130
but things like change logs

00:45:08.130 --> 00:45:11.220
and tech support
forums, for example.

00:45:11.220 --> 00:45:13.650
The ambitious question
to ask here it seems

00:45:13.650 --> 00:45:18.640
to me is how would we
archive digital culture?

00:45:18.640 --> 00:45:21.710
One project I'm working on right
now is to collect snapshots

00:45:21.710 --> 00:45:26.470
of entire computers and to save
them in sort of time capsules

00:45:26.470 --> 00:45:29.760
that capture not only
specific projects,

00:45:29.760 --> 00:45:32.120
but an entire way
of working, right?

00:45:32.120 --> 00:45:35.610
These may or may not be
interesting a couple decades

00:45:35.610 --> 00:45:39.730
from now as kind of
case studies, we'll see.

00:45:39.730 --> 00:45:43.260
I'll end by noting a commonality
between the projects I showed.

00:45:43.260 --> 00:45:46.970
My own privileged position
with direct access to files

00:45:46.970 --> 00:45:49.310
and the people who created them.

00:45:49.310 --> 00:45:52.970
My sort of final question here
is how can we set-up archives

00:45:52.970 --> 00:45:55.100
that recreate as much

00:45:55.100 --> 00:45:57.480
as possible this
privileged position

00:45:57.480 --> 00:45:59.510
for every researcher
approaching an archive?

00:45:59.510 --> 00:46:02.510
How can we allow a
feeling of direct access

00:46:02.510 --> 00:46:04.880
or of a window onto a culture?

00:46:04.880 --> 00:46:07.560
I suspect that this would
require a very particular type

00:46:07.560 --> 00:46:10.550
of archive that we don't
actually see very often.

00:46:10.550 --> 00:46:13.510
Okay, thank you.

