00:54:10.620 --> 00:54:12.750
which isn't mine either.

00:54:12.750 --> 00:54:18.130
And I think the point is, you
know, the point I want to make

00:54:18.130 --> 00:54:22.320
about the Rosetta Stone is --

00:54:22.320 --> 00:54:25.660
I guess are there any
linguists in the audience?

00:54:25.660 --> 00:54:26.960
Okay, mostly architects.

00:54:26.960 --> 00:54:30.110
So obviously the
purpose of an object

00:54:30.110 --> 00:54:34.220
like the Rosetta Stone isn't
just to archive itself,

00:54:34.220 --> 00:54:38.420
it's to serve as an archive
for all possible languages --

00:54:38.420 --> 00:54:41.160
what do you want to
say, sort of sentences

00:54:41.160 --> 00:54:43.470
or configurations associated
with those languages, right?

00:54:43.470 --> 00:54:45.670
That's why it's so important.

00:54:45.670 --> 00:54:47.640
So the question that
I think I would pose

00:54:47.640 --> 00:54:50.880
and I think Andrew did
this a little bit, as well,

00:54:50.880 --> 00:54:56.430
is can we not just
archive a specific object,

00:54:56.430 --> 00:54:59.730
maybe it's been representation,
but get a little bit deeper sort

00:54:59.730 --> 00:55:05.150
of in terms of the forensics
of understanding the DNA

00:55:05.150 --> 00:55:07.820
of that particular
typology, right?

00:55:07.820 --> 00:55:10.980
So what do all GSA
courthouses have in common?

00:55:10.980 --> 00:55:14.270
How could you compare
them to each other?

00:55:14.270 --> 00:55:16.600
Is there a way of
sort of qualifying

00:55:16.600 --> 00:55:18.680
or quantifying those
features, right?

00:55:18.680 --> 00:55:25.130
So there is some really
interesting research work

00:55:25.130 --> 00:55:28.480
that is really about --
I'll just cut forward --

00:55:28.480 --> 00:55:31.700
is about sort of understanding
the languages of design.

00:55:31.700 --> 00:55:34.810
It goes by a special term
called shape grammars,

00:55:34.810 --> 00:55:37.060
some of you may have heard of
this, but it really is sort

00:55:37.060 --> 00:55:41.890
of a direct descendent of
computational linguistics.

00:55:41.890 --> 00:55:45.040
And I guess I would
just compare these two

00:55:45.040 --> 00:55:46.370
because this is worth
digging into a little bit.

00:55:46.370 --> 00:55:49.600
I learned the diagram on the
left when I was in high school,

00:55:49.600 --> 00:55:51.350
that probably dates me.

00:55:51.350 --> 00:55:55.390
I should say I didn't learn
it, the English teacher brought

00:55:55.390 --> 00:55:57.590
that up one afternoon,
nobody could figure

00:55:57.590 --> 00:55:59.530
out what he was talking
about and he dropped it.

00:55:59.530 --> 00:56:01.970
And I imagine a lot of you
have had a similar experience.

00:56:01.970 --> 00:56:07.060
So Norm Chomsky, known for a
lot of important work but came

00:56:07.060 --> 00:56:08.490
up with this epiphany

00:56:08.490 --> 00:56:10.840
that really all sentences
are structured

00:56:10.840 --> 00:56:12.400
as these binary decompositions.

00:56:12.400 --> 00:56:14.330
So a sentence can
be decomponented

00:56:14.330 --> 00:56:17.050
into its noun phrase and its
verb phrase, the verb phrase

00:56:17.050 --> 00:56:19.160
in terms of a verb
and a noun, whatever,

00:56:19.160 --> 00:56:21.610
a participle I think -- you guys
might know better than me --

00:56:21.610 --> 00:56:23.160
and they sort of
cascade down, right?

00:56:23.160 --> 00:56:26.410
There's this substitution
from a high level object

00:56:26.410 --> 00:56:29.830
and its decomposition into
richer and richer sort

00:56:29.830 --> 00:56:31.640
of substructures, right?

00:56:31.640 --> 00:56:34.550
So if you tee it up
that way the idea

00:56:34.550 --> 00:56:38.450
that there might be some sort
of way of decomposing a project

00:56:38.450 --> 00:56:40.660
into its constituent
components and then further

00:56:40.660 --> 00:56:43.270
and then further and
understanding that structure

00:56:43.270 --> 00:56:45.640
as you go makes some
sort of sense

00:56:45.640 --> 00:56:48.200
and that's really the basis

00:56:48.200 --> 00:56:51.530
of the shape grammar
canon, if you will.

00:56:51.530 --> 00:56:54.800
So left and right are two
examples I'll show you.

00:56:54.800 --> 00:56:58.750
Let me see, let me
go to a specific --

00:56:58.750 --> 00:57:01.590
well, here's the theory,
which is that it's

00:57:01.590 --> 00:57:06.660
about again these substitutions,
every shape, every building,

00:57:06.660 --> 00:57:10.200
every project can be decomposed
into replacement rules

00:57:10.200 --> 00:57:12.840
that architects might replace
one thing with another.

00:57:12.840 --> 00:57:15.360
I see a square, I rotate
it, blah, blah, blah.

00:57:15.360 --> 00:57:17.640
I can find that shape
in my design,

00:57:17.640 --> 00:57:19.250
I can do that replacement.

00:57:19.250 --> 00:57:22.380
And so a lot of the work about
documenting, this has been done

00:57:22.380 --> 00:57:25.390
with Frank Lloyd Wright
projects and Palladian Villas

00:57:25.390 --> 00:57:28.700
and the list goes on and on,
but you can essentially sort

00:57:28.700 --> 00:57:33.880
of archive that set of rules
and use it to play back

00:57:33.880 --> 00:57:38.180
for all kinds of different
projects of that typology.

00:57:38.180 --> 00:57:40.610
So here's some work
that ties directly

00:57:40.610 --> 00:57:43.110
into the CourtsWeb project,

00:57:43.110 --> 00:57:45.440
which is looking at
Meise courthouses.

00:57:45.440 --> 00:57:47.540
As far as I understand
there's quite a few of them.

00:57:47.540 --> 00:57:50.640
On the left are the
original sketches from Meise,

00:57:50.640 --> 00:57:54.170
on the right are those
generated typologies

00:57:54.170 --> 00:57:59.670
and those are generated by this
list of these substitution rules

00:57:59.670 --> 00:58:02.460
that you can apply to take
the overall courthouse,

00:58:02.460 --> 00:58:05.310
maybe split it up into,
Lord knows, the public

00:58:05.310 --> 00:58:07.800
and the private and then
down to other refinements.

00:58:07.800 --> 00:58:09.100
So even down to things

00:58:09.100 --> 00:58:13.650
like actual construction
typologies, right?

00:58:13.650 --> 00:58:16.850
So here's again that set of
rules being applied and the fact

00:58:16.850 --> 00:58:18.230
that you can apply
to a whole bunch

00:58:18.230 --> 00:58:19.800
of different possible
configurations

00:58:19.800 --> 00:58:21.600
of this Meise courthouse.

00:58:21.600 --> 00:58:26.390
Last thing I'll show you is some
work that actually is just part

00:58:26.390 --> 00:58:29.820
of what I teach to all the
students at Georgia Tech.

00:58:29.820 --> 00:58:33.740
And it's a little bit the same
idea and it's using Grasshopper,

00:58:33.740 --> 00:58:38.120
which I think many of
you will know is a sort

00:58:38.120 --> 00:58:42.200
of visual scripting
add-on to Rhino.

00:58:42.200 --> 00:58:44.560
How many of you have
heard of Grasshopper?

00:58:44.560 --> 00:58:47.500
Okay, and it's a very easy way
to do some of the crazy stuff

00:58:47.500 --> 00:58:50.150
that Andrew was talking about.

00:58:50.150 --> 00:58:54.040
So basically you can
generate scripts by dragging

00:58:54.040 --> 00:58:57.300
and dropping these blocks and
then you make modifications

00:58:57.300 --> 00:58:59.060
to the blocks and it
generates these forms.

00:58:59.060 --> 00:59:02.300
But I think for me what's
interesting and what I try

00:59:02.300 --> 00:59:05.160
to force the students to believe
is that you can actually use

00:59:05.160 --> 00:59:09.350
that as a diagraming tool in and
of itself for the organization

00:59:09.350 --> 00:59:11.380
of the logic of the projects.

00:59:11.380 --> 00:59:13.740
And we do a number
of case studies

00:59:13.740 --> 00:59:18.160
of historical projects
using these frameworks,

00:59:18.160 --> 00:59:23.190
and there's kind of a high level
hypothesis that we actually,

00:59:23.190 --> 00:59:26.210
that I brought from
Gary's work which says,

00:59:26.210 --> 00:59:28.930
and this may sound
crazy or simple

00:59:28.930 --> 00:59:30.400
or really dumbing it down.

00:59:30.400 --> 00:59:33.270
But all projects
can be decomposed

00:59:33.270 --> 00:59:37.340
into three high level systems,
the exterior volume of it,

00:59:37.340 --> 00:59:41.370
the floor, top of floor
planes, top of slab planes,

00:59:41.370 --> 00:59:43.170
and the structural grid.

00:59:43.170 --> 00:59:46.290
And once you have those three
canonical systems you mix

00:59:46.290 --> 00:59:48.630
and match them and then
you get sort of the frames

00:59:48.630 --> 00:59:50.080
that the mullions go in,

00:59:50.080 --> 00:59:52.130
the core goes in,
those kind of things.

00:59:52.130 --> 00:59:55.700
So there is this kind of natural
hierarchy of all projects

00:59:55.700 --> 00:59:59.320
of that decomposition and
just we actually can look

00:59:59.320 --> 01:00:02.500
at some core templates and
how those things play out,

01:00:02.500 --> 01:00:05.040
but we look at different
sort of typologies, towers,

01:00:05.040 --> 01:00:06.400
grids, stadium, stations.

01:00:06.400 --> 01:00:08.310
We actually give out
these little templates

01:00:08.310 --> 01:00:09.690
and then the students
