01:13:01.620 --> 01:13:06.800
and the steps standard was
supposed to be straightforward

01:13:06.800 --> 01:13:09.780
and unambiguous and all
these kinds of things

01:13:09.780 --> 01:13:13.670
but these systems didn't
interoperate at all.

01:13:13.670 --> 01:13:17.580
So, and actually I think I'd
said this a little earlier,

01:13:17.580 --> 01:13:20.990
but myself and some other folks
in this industry got together

01:13:20.990 --> 01:13:23.990
and we said, well, how
can we test this software?

01:13:23.990 --> 01:13:29.050
And we didn't like those words
like compliant and conformant

01:13:29.050 --> 01:13:31.510
and things like that
because I think if you look

01:13:31.510 --> 01:13:35.860
out in the general software
industry there are certainly

01:13:35.860 --> 01:13:40.030
examples of software that's
conformant or compliant

01:13:40.030 --> 01:13:42.040
but not interoperable at all.

01:13:42.040 --> 01:13:45.670
So interoperability
was our number one goal

01:13:45.670 --> 01:13:49.770
in starting the CAx
implementor forum.

01:13:49.770 --> 01:13:54.130
There's currently three
hosting organizations of it.

01:13:54.130 --> 01:13:56.260
The organization
that I'm on contract

01:13:56.260 --> 01:13:58.320
to is called PDES, Incorporated.

01:13:58.320 --> 01:14:03.800
It's primarily an aerospace
and defense consortium.

01:14:03.800 --> 01:14:06.650
Prostep is a project
under PDES, Inc.

01:14:06.650 --> 01:14:13.090
Prostep ivip is I would call
them a German automotive

01:14:13.090 --> 01:14:15.070
consortium, but they
probably prefer

01:14:15.070 --> 01:14:18.670
to be called a European
automotive consortium,

01:14:18.670 --> 01:14:20.750
heavy German influence.

01:14:20.750 --> 01:14:25.520
And then AFNet, and don't
ask me what that stands for

01:14:25.520 --> 01:14:30.750
and it's probably French anyway,
but they're kind of a trains,

01:14:30.750 --> 01:14:34.340
planes and automobile
industry group of France.

01:14:34.340 --> 01:14:39.180
But those are the
organizations that host us.

01:14:39.180 --> 01:14:43.290
The group is composed
of computer aided design

01:14:43.290 --> 01:14:45.590
and computer aided
engineering vendors

01:14:45.590 --> 01:14:48.000
and also what we call
third-party vendors,

01:14:48.000 --> 01:14:50.330
which are the translation
software vendors.

01:14:50.330 --> 01:14:53.520
They don't, a third-party vendor
doesn't have any authoring

01:14:53.520 --> 01:14:58.850
software, they just change
the gender of a native file

01:14:58.850 --> 01:15:02.370
to a neutral file or
something like that.

01:15:02.370 --> 01:15:06.960
It is a closed group,
we call it a sandbox.

01:15:06.960 --> 01:15:12.750
We do not release results of a
particular vendor to the world

01:15:12.750 --> 01:15:14.800
or to our member organizations.

01:15:14.800 --> 01:15:18.870
The only results they see
are kind of rolled up,

01:15:18.870 --> 01:15:21.500
so how well did we do
on geometric accuracy

01:15:21.500 --> 01:15:22.800
or something like that.

01:15:22.800 --> 01:15:26.680
And so it is a trusted
environment,

01:15:26.680 --> 01:15:30.620
and I don't think
you see this much

01:15:30.620 --> 01:15:34.380
in other software
development groups,

01:15:34.380 --> 01:15:37.820
but you'll actually
see somebody from --

01:15:37.820 --> 01:15:39.120
I'm just going to
make this up --

01:15:39.120 --> 01:15:43.460
Deso Systems helping out
somebody from Siemens NX

01:15:43.460 --> 01:15:48.140
or Solid Works or whatever, and
it's kind of a neat environment.

01:15:48.140 --> 01:15:52.720
We launched this in '99,
that was kind of part

01:15:52.720 --> 01:15:54.150
of the history lessons.

01:15:54.150 --> 01:15:57.110
We've actually done 40 rounds
of testing on the CAD side

01:15:57.110 --> 01:16:00.350
and we're just starting
on the CAE side,

01:16:00.350 --> 01:16:05.090
and really our primary mission
is to meet industry's needs

01:16:05.090 --> 01:16:15.560
by providing them with these
interoperable products.

01:16:15.560 --> 01:16:19.420
I already said we test
on a closed environment.

01:16:19.420 --> 01:16:22.450
We don't let any
specific results out.

01:16:22.450 --> 01:16:27.730
All the participants are
testing alpha and beta software,

01:16:27.730 --> 01:16:31.710
it's pre-production, so this
early detection of errors

01:16:31.710 --> 01:16:34.850
in their software
actually provides them

01:16:34.850 --> 01:16:37.720
with a faster development cycle.

01:16:37.720 --> 01:16:44.530
One other thing that I think
is a big benefit of this is

01:16:44.530 --> 01:16:47.010
that we actually
test the standard

01:16:47.010 --> 01:16:48.380
as it's being developed,

01:16:48.380 --> 01:16:50.700
and you'll see a
chart a little later,

01:16:50.700 --> 01:16:56.640
but the current steps standard
we're working on is AP242

01:16:56.640 --> 01:17:00.710
and it was as soon as
we had a data model

01:17:00.710 --> 01:17:05.490
of AP242 we started testing
it and yet it's going

01:17:05.490 --> 01:17:09.430
through the ISO ballot
process at the same time,

01:17:09.430 --> 01:17:11.520
so it's not even an
international standard yet.

01:17:11.520 --> 01:17:16.620
So we tested the standard
while it was being developed,

01:17:16.620 --> 01:17:18.780
we provided input back to them

01:17:18.780 --> 01:17:21.670
so that they could
improve the standard

01:17:21.670 --> 01:17:27.540
and get rid of the bugs in it.

01:17:27.540 --> 01:17:29.560
We call this CAx-IF on a page,

01:17:29.560 --> 01:17:34.570
but up in the upper left there
we have the user companies

01:17:34.570 --> 01:17:38.620
and then there are a broad
range of types of companies.

01:17:38.620 --> 01:17:42.730
There are aerospace and defense,
there are automotive, you know,

01:17:42.730 --> 01:17:48.890
shipbuilding, you name it,
but they kind of provide us

01:17:48.890 --> 01:17:50.540
with their requirements.

01:17:50.540 --> 01:17:54.540
And a relatively recent
requirement is that we have

01:17:54.540 --> 01:17:57.680
to have geometric and
dimensional tolerances

01:17:57.680 --> 01:18:00.520
in the step-based products.

01:18:00.520 --> 01:18:07.430
So we go off and see how hard
that's going to be to do and see

01:18:07.430 --> 01:18:09.460
if it's in the data
model, the group down there

01:18:09.460 --> 01:18:13.490
in the lower left, the ISO.

01:18:13.490 --> 01:18:16.880
And then we also get test
models from the user companies

01:18:16.880 --> 01:18:21.130
to do our testing with,
and we go off and test it.

01:18:21.130 --> 01:18:26.490
And so the user companies get
interoperable software back.

01:18:26.490 --> 01:18:30.920
The standards groups they get
standardization issues fed back

01:18:30.920 --> 01:18:32.220
to them.

01:18:32.220 --> 01:18:34.980
And just to the general world
over there on the bottom right,

01:18:34.980 --> 01:18:37.610
you know, they get
commercial products that work.

01:18:37.610 --> 01:18:43.450
So I'm not going to spend any
time on this, this is kind

01:18:43.450 --> 01:18:48.990
of the scope of AP242, but
it's all those kinds of things

01:18:48.990 --> 01:18:53.000
that they use in a
mechanical design context.

01:18:53.000 --> 01:18:58.150
And an important word there
is managed model based 3D

01:18:58.150 --> 01:19:01.520
engineering, so it's
designed to be managed

01:19:01.520 --> 01:19:03.770
by a PDM or a PLM system.

01:19:03.770 --> 01:19:08.780
Again, it has all the
data necessary to do that.

01:19:08.780 --> 01:19:15.390
And, like I said, this is the
kind of the history of AP242

01:19:15.390 --> 01:19:17.060
and testing it, if you will.

01:19:17.060 --> 01:19:20.390
And I think I said we were
on the 40th round of testing,

01:19:20.390 --> 01:19:26.190
but the development of AP242
started at the end of 2010.

01:19:26.190 --> 01:19:31.640
And along the left-hand side
those are all the various ISO

01:19:31.640 --> 01:19:35.060
valid steps you'd
have to go through.

01:19:35.060 --> 01:19:37.540
And so we've been testing
it all the way along,

01:19:37.540 --> 01:19:42.310
and actually sometimes
we've actually been ahead

01:19:42.310 --> 01:19:46.010
of the standard and we'll
see things that aren't

01:19:46.010 --> 01:19:49.110
in the standard and we'll
just make up a data model

01:19:49.110 --> 01:19:52.290
and stick it into the main data
model ourselves and go ahead

01:19:52.290 --> 01:19:55.570
and test it and then feed that
back to the standards folks.

01:19:57.190 --> 01:20:02.520
Regarding our methodology,

01:20:02.520 --> 01:20:07.250
the steps standard uses both
express and XML schemas.

01:20:07.250 --> 01:20:10.740
XML is primarily
used for what I kind

01:20:10.740 --> 01:20:15.070
of consider the softer
stuff, the metadata

01:20:15.070 --> 01:20:18.260
and the part number,
stuff like that.

01:20:18.260 --> 01:20:20.900
And then we use the
express, it is primarily used

01:20:20.900 --> 01:20:24.270
for the geometry and
the complex stuff

01:20:24.270 --> 01:20:30.830
because express is a lot more
richer modeling language.

01:20:30.830 --> 01:20:34.320
We also provide these documents
called recommended practices

01:20:34.320 --> 01:20:37.250
documents, and it's kind
of a cookbook approach

01:20:37.250 --> 01:20:41.110
on how you implement
the steps standards.

01:20:41.110 --> 01:20:43.850
And, as I said earlier,
these standards were supposed

01:20:43.850 --> 01:20:47.850
to have been unambiguous,
but obviously they weren't.

01:20:47.850 --> 01:20:50.920
And there's a lot of
times in the standard

01:20:50.920 --> 01:20:54.310
where there's multiple
paths you can take

01:20:54.310 --> 01:21:00.600
or you don't really know what
kind of value is expected

01:21:00.600 --> 01:21:01.900
or something of that nature.

01:21:01.900 --> 01:21:05.560
So we write these recommended
practices documents based upon

01:21:05.560 --> 01:21:08.590
discussion we have with
all the software developers

01:21:08.590 --> 01:21:11.430
and it's an agreement,
if you will.

01:21:11.430 --> 01:21:17.060
And then the test
case definitions.

01:21:17.060 --> 01:21:20.420
When the vendor produces a step
file based upon a particular

01:21:20.420 --> 01:21:25.340
functionality we test it for
syntax, so is it conformant

01:21:25.340 --> 01:21:29.220
to the schema, and typically
that's kind of as far

01:21:29.220 --> 01:21:32.110
as conformance testing goes,

01:21:32.110 --> 01:21:34.250
just is it conformant
to the schema.

01:21:34.250 --> 01:21:37.670
But we also test it for
structure and semantics,

01:21:37.670 --> 01:21:41.060
and we kind of consider that
to be conformant to our --

01:21:41.060 --> 01:21:43.470
and I don't like to even
use that word conformance,

01:21:43.470 --> 01:21:49.470
but applicable or it lends
itself or it follows along

01:21:49.470 --> 01:21:51.800
with the recommended
practices documents.

01:21:51.800 --> 01:21:57.330
And actually we get a
lot of I think the IFC

01:21:57.330 --> 01:22:00.680
and BIM folks have had a lot of
interaction with the NIST folks

01:22:00.680 --> 01:22:05.220
over the years and kind of
the same help, if you will,

01:22:05.220 --> 01:22:11.010
so and NIST helps
us out with this.

01:22:11.010 --> 01:22:14.480
Anyway, so these step files
are submitted and they're found

01:22:14.480 --> 01:22:18.300
