01:26:14.150 --> 01:26:19.570
Okay, the first part of my
presentation is the case

01:26:19.570 --> 01:26:22.290
for software as infrastructure.

01:26:22.290 --> 01:26:25.270
So, well, a sneak preview.

01:26:25.270 --> 01:26:29.870
So Susan Leistar, who is an
information infrastructure

01:26:29.870 --> 01:26:33.140
scholar, sadly is
no longer with us,

01:26:33.140 --> 01:26:36.030
wrote in a paper called The
Ethnography of Infrastructure,

01:26:36.030 --> 01:26:38.560
quote, people commonly
envision infrastructure

01:26:38.560 --> 01:26:40.270
as a system of substrates.

01:26:40.270 --> 01:26:43.040
It is by definition invisible,
it's part of the background

01:26:43.040 --> 01:26:45.590
for other kinds of
work, end quote.

01:26:45.590 --> 01:26:46.980
Infrastructure is
a fundamentally

01:26:46.980 --> 01:26:48.460
relational concept.

01:26:48.460 --> 01:26:51.020
The cook considers the water
system as working infrastructure

01:26:51.020 --> 01:26:52.320
and a role to making dinner,

01:26:52.320 --> 01:26:55.140
while for the city
planner it's a variable

01:26:55.140 --> 01:26:59.020
in a complex planning process
or a target for repair.

01:26:59.020 --> 01:27:02.270
Star and her colleague completed
a study in the early 1990s

01:27:02.270 --> 01:27:05.840
on an online community
called WORM, and concluded

01:27:05.840 --> 01:27:08.170
that infrastructure has
several key characteristics.

01:27:08.170 --> 01:27:09.470
So this is their model.

01:27:09.470 --> 01:27:11.810
And I'm going to present the
case that software has all

01:27:11.810 --> 01:27:14.770
of these characteristics with
examples where appropriate

01:27:14.770 --> 01:27:16.070
from architectural design

01:27:16.070 --> 01:27:17.700
and engineering
scholar-practitioners,

01:27:17.700 --> 01:27:20.640
as well as much broader examples
provided by the cofounder

01:27:20.640 --> 01:27:23.720
of Netscape, Mark Anderson,
in his 2011 article,

01:27:23.720 --> 01:27:25.460
Software is Eating the World.

01:27:25.460 --> 01:27:29.510
The examples still hold true
and, frankly, even more so.

01:27:29.510 --> 01:27:33.310
So software is embedded,
it's sunk into and inside

01:27:33.310 --> 01:27:36.420
of other structures, social
arrangements and technologies.

01:27:36.420 --> 01:27:38.440
Anderson writes, more
and more major businesses

01:27:38.440 --> 01:27:40.580
and industries are being
around software delivered

01:27:40.580 --> 01:27:43.630
as online services from
movies to agriculture,

01:27:43.630 --> 01:27:47.400
to national defense,
to global finance.

01:27:47.400 --> 01:27:52.000
Mack U. Allen [assumed
spelling], reviewing

01:27:52.000 --> 01:27:56.020
and exhibit entitled,
Architecture, Architectural

01:27:56.020 --> 01:28:00.530
and Architecture with a capital
A, describes as evidenced

01:28:00.530 --> 01:28:01.830
by the works included

01:28:01.830 --> 01:28:03.320
in the exhibit how
software is not a part

01:28:03.320 --> 01:28:06.650
of the specific workflow or
phase of architectural design,

01:28:06.650 --> 01:28:10.790
but rather that it's embedded
into a creative work routine.

01:28:10.790 --> 01:28:14.480
Software is transparent
and specifically

01:28:14.480 --> 01:28:17.260
in this context meaning that it
doesn't have to be reassembled

01:28:17.260 --> 01:28:20.090
or reinvented each
time or for each task,

01:28:20.090 --> 01:28:22.990
but that it invisibly
supports those tasks.

01:28:22.990 --> 01:28:25.380
Anderson writes, on the backend
software programming tools

01:28:25.380 --> 01:28:27.120
and internet based
services make it easy

01:28:27.120 --> 01:28:29.380
to launch new global
software powered startups

01:28:29.380 --> 01:28:31.990
in many industries
without the need to invest

01:28:31.990 --> 01:28:35.890
in new infrastructure
and train new employees.

01:28:35.890 --> 01:28:38.260
Software has reach and scope,

01:28:38.260 --> 01:28:41.490
beyond a single event
or one site practice.

01:28:41.490 --> 01:28:43.420
Anderson writes, software
is also eating much

01:28:43.420 --> 01:28:46.620
of the value chain of industries
that are widely viewed

01:28:46.620 --> 01:28:49.080
as primarily existing
in the physical world.

01:28:49.080 --> 01:28:52.110
Software runs engines, it
controls safety features,

01:28:52.110 --> 01:28:54.130
it guides drivers
to destinations,

01:28:54.130 --> 01:28:56.890
it powers logistics and
distribution capabilities

01:28:56.890 --> 01:28:59.430
of FedEx, Walmart and the like.

01:28:59.430 --> 01:29:03.000
As is evidenced by discussions
here today the built environment

01:29:03.000 --> 01:29:06.220
often begins in a
software environment.

01:29:06.220 --> 01:29:08.350
Software is learned as
part of a membership,

01:29:08.350 --> 01:29:11.140
so similar to the
art of drafting,

01:29:11.140 --> 01:29:13.760
specific planning documentation
for the built environment

01:29:13.760 --> 01:29:16.640
and different forms of modeling
certain types of software

01:29:16.640 --> 01:29:19.280
or specific uses of
that software are part

01:29:19.280 --> 01:29:20.820
of the repertoire
of a profession

01:29:20.820 --> 01:29:24.280
or a community of practice.

01:29:24.280 --> 01:29:26.060
Software is the embodiment
of standards,

01:29:26.060 --> 01:29:30.050
so speaking to Katie's
analysis in her dissertation

01:29:30.050 --> 01:29:31.960
of architectural
practice as associated

01:29:31.960 --> 01:29:34.810
with technical system, a
practice has specific needs

01:29:34.810 --> 01:29:37.310
and standardized
workflows or business rules,

01:29:37.310 --> 01:29:40.260
some of which can be translated
into the functional requirements

01:29:40.260 --> 01:29:42.320
of software applications.

01:29:42.320 --> 01:29:44.470
These applications as
embodiments of standards

01:29:44.470 --> 01:29:47.570
and conventions have their own
impacts on the daily practice

01:29:47.570 --> 01:29:50.280
as they are adopted and adapted.

01:29:50.280 --> 01:29:52.030
The use and reuse
of these software

01:29:52.030 --> 01:29:55.160
and resulting digital objects
may shape the need or demand

01:29:55.160 --> 01:29:59.090
for changes or enhancements
to the software in the future.

01:29:59.090 --> 01:30:01.950
Software is built on
an installed base.

01:30:01.950 --> 01:30:03.990
All new infrastructure
wrestles with the inertia

01:30:03.990 --> 01:30:05.760
of the installed base.

01:30:05.760 --> 01:30:08.720
Software is always wrestling
with existing practices,

01:30:08.720 --> 01:30:12.350
user expectations and tools.

01:30:12.350 --> 01:30:14.300
Software is fixed in
modular increments,

01:30:14.300 --> 01:30:16.120
not all at once or globally.

01:30:16.120 --> 01:30:17.750
Because software
exists in a universe

01:30:17.750 --> 01:30:20.150
of dependencies you're
always pursuing a fix

01:30:20.150 --> 01:30:22.030
that is the most well contained

01:30:22.030 --> 01:30:24.750
or most loosely coupled
to everything else.

01:30:24.750 --> 01:30:28.250
The fix for the Windows XP users
during the WannaCry ransomware

01:30:28.250 --> 01:30:32.520
event in May 2017 was a patch,
not a comprehensive upgrade

01:30:32.520 --> 01:30:35.120
for those users from
XP to Windows 10.

01:30:35.120 --> 01:30:36.820
What is the smallest
change we can make

01:30:36.820 --> 01:30:38.740
that will repair the
system or bring it back

01:30:38.740 --> 01:30:40.810
into an operational state?

01:30:40.810 --> 01:30:44.190
Because of this software is
in a state of ongoing repair.

01:30:44.190 --> 01:30:48.590
And then finally software
becomes visible on breakdown

01:30:48.590 --> 01:30:50.150
and this is what
will problematize.

01:30:50.150 --> 01:30:52.500
And I don't know
if you can see it,

01:30:52.500 --> 01:30:55.970
but the infrastructure is
showing in that photograph.

01:30:55.970 --> 01:30:58.370
It got cut-off a little bit.

01:30:58.370 --> 01:31:00.670
Your infrastructure is showing.

01:31:01.970 --> 01:31:04.540
[laughter] So software
can break, it has bugs,

01:31:04.540 --> 01:31:06.910
but breakdown doesn't
map as well as the others

01:31:06.910 --> 01:31:08.600
because software is so embedded.

01:31:08.600 --> 01:31:12.260
So to use Anderson's words
consumptive of all structures

01:31:12.260 --> 01:31:14.480
in industries that we
can't decouple the software

01:31:14.480 --> 01:31:17.090
from other substrates in
the system including users,

01:31:17.090 --> 01:31:21.090
the network, the regulatory
framework and the industry.

01:31:21.090 --> 01:31:23.890
I argue that what we mean
by software breakdown

01:31:23.890 --> 01:31:25.860
in today's context is
much bigger than that.

01:31:25.860 --> 01:31:28.990
It's better understood
as the access breakdown

01:31:28.990 --> 01:31:31.020
or the inability to
support meaningful access

01:31:31.020 --> 01:31:32.830
to digital information.

01:31:32.830 --> 01:31:34.360
This could be reproducible
science

01:31:34.360 --> 01:31:37.510
and social scientific research
or as McKenzie Smith wrote

01:31:37.510 --> 01:31:41.540
in her 2012 article for AIA
Online, quote, the need to refer

01:31:41.540 --> 01:31:44.130
to an old design, consult
a change order or ASI

01:31:44.130 --> 01:31:47.030
from a completed project,
or consider an addition

01:31:47.030 --> 01:31:49.230
to an old building, end quote.

01:31:49.230 --> 01:31:50.890
The access breakdown reveals

01:31:50.890 --> 01:31:54.550
or makes visible the social
structures and practices

01:31:54.550 --> 01:31:57.020
in which the software
is embedded.

01:31:57.020 --> 01:31:59.490
I'll repeat that, the
access breakdown reveals

01:31:59.490 --> 01:32:01.870
or makes visible the social
structures and practices

01:32:01.870 --> 01:32:03.820
in which the software
is embedded.

01:32:03.820 --> 01:32:06.140
The access breakdown is
a comprehensive breakdown

01:32:06.140 --> 01:32:09.190
of social structures to
support information access,

01:32:09.190 --> 01:32:11.840
communication, legal
systems and the market.

01:32:11.840 --> 01:32:15.760
And when these social structures
breakdown they produce

01:32:15.760 --> 01:32:19.470
and necessitate system
level change.

01:32:19.470 --> 01:32:22.570
So a little bit more about
the access breakdown.

01:32:22.570 --> 01:32:25.350
Our cultural record is
increasingly made-up

01:32:25.350 --> 01:32:27.480
of complex digital
logics as evidenced

01:32:27.480 --> 01:32:29.750
by discussions here
today, which are coupled

01:32:29.750 --> 01:32:33.400
to software both proprietary
and nonproprietary.

01:32:33.400 --> 01:32:35.220
And I really, really,
really, really,

01:32:35.220 --> 01:32:36.770
really wish that I could go

01:32:36.770 --> 01:32:39.390
into this software
preservation history,

01:32:39.390 --> 01:32:43.480
but this is a timeline
that's complementary to all

01:32:43.480 --> 01:32:47.410
of the amazing work that
Elisa and Tim and Katie shared

01:32:47.410 --> 01:32:51.620
with you earlier today,
that looks at the history

01:32:51.620 --> 01:32:55.310
of just the software
preservation discourse and just

01:32:55.310 --> 01:32:57.110
in information science,

01:32:57.110 --> 01:32:59.500
computing history,
and the archives.

01:32:59.500 --> 01:33:02.870
So our culture is
increasingly made-up

01:33:02.870 --> 01:33:05.450
of complex digital
objects or what Peterson,

01:33:05.450 --> 01:33:09.100
Trudy Huskein Peterson [assumed
spelling] to be exact, termed,

01:33:09.100 --> 01:33:11.830
quote, software dependent
in 1985.

01:33:11.830 --> 01:33:13.780
Evidenced by the 30
plus year discourse

01:33:13.780 --> 01:33:16.150
and information studies,
history of computing

01:33:16.150 --> 01:33:18.930
and cultural memory preservation
alone, and that's not

01:33:18.930 --> 01:33:21.120
to say there aren't other
discourse of communities talking

01:33:21.120 --> 01:33:22.880
about this for a long time.

01:33:22.880 --> 01:33:25.950
The access breakdown, like
most infrastructure breakdowns,

01:33:25.950 --> 01:33:29.560
is relatively to software
slow in the making.

01:33:29.560 --> 01:33:33.490
So the access breakdown
necessitates system level change

01:33:33.490 --> 01:33:37.470
that acknowledges
software as infrastructure.

01:33:37.470 --> 01:33:42.410
System level change, so in 1995
Liam Bannon [assumed spelling]

01:33:42.410 --> 01:33:47.040
posted a short piece in ACM
called, The Politics of Design.

01:33:47.040 --> 01:33:48.340
Quote, the development

01:33:48.340 --> 01:33:50.580
of computer based applications
requires the collaboration

01:33:50.580 --> 01:33:53.560
or involvement of a variety
of distinctive communities,

01:33:53.560 --> 01:33:55.280
workers with different
skills using different

01:33:55.280 --> 01:33:57.160
representational frameworks.

01:33:57.160 --> 01:34:00.200
This poses a number of
problems which can't be removed

01:34:00.200 --> 01:34:02.240
by simply ensuring
good communication.

01:34:02.240 --> 01:34:04.840
He argues it's more
fundamental than that,

01:34:04.840 --> 01:34:07.470
it arises out of different
practices of the groups.

01:34:07.470 --> 01:34:08.970
So how to construct a shared

01:34:08.970 --> 01:34:11.560
or common information space
among these groups is seen

01:34:11.560 --> 01:34:14.520
as a central concern.

01:34:14.520 --> 01:34:15.940
Collective impact is a model

01:34:15.940 --> 01:34:19.270
for understanding
system level change.

01:34:19.270 --> 01:34:23.020
Collective impact has
five distinct components.

01:34:23.020 --> 01:34:25.510
The common agenda, so engaging
all of the stakeholders

01:34:25.510 --> 01:34:27.510
around a problem area
and helping them to come

01:34:27.510 --> 01:34:30.600
to an agreement upon a common
vision or goal for change.

01:34:30.600 --> 01:34:32.100
Shared measurement and data

01:34:32.100 --> 01:34:35.010
that helps each group determine
what specific incremental steps

01:34:35.010 --> 01:34:38.930
it can take to continue forward
progress at the system level.

01:34:38.930 --> 01:34:42.000
Mutually reinforcing activities
that meet the vested interest

01:34:42.000 --> 01:34:44.140
in economic drivers of
each stakeholder group

01:34:44.140 --> 01:34:46.590
and the system, itself.

01:34:46.590 --> 01:34:48.530
Constant communication
and refining of goals

01:34:48.530 --> 01:34:51.520
of the stakeholders, both
individually and as a system.

01:34:51.520 --> 01:34:54.980
And a lightweight backbone
comprising focused facilitators

01:34:54.980 --> 01:34:58.080
providing the necessary
connection work.

01:34:58.080 --> 01:35:00.990
The Software Preservation
Network is building capacity

01:35:00.990 --> 01:35:03.170
to serve as a lightweight
backbone organization

01:35:03.170 --> 01:35:05.660
that embodies and supports
a collective impact approach

01:35:05.660 --> 01:35:07.500
to software preservation.

01:35:07.500 --> 01:35:11.770
SPIN was first discussed in a
public forum in 2014 as an idea,

01:35:11.770 --> 01:35:15.570
an idea that was conceptualized
as a logical extension

01:35:15.570 --> 01:35:18.610
of the work spanning that
roughly 30 plus years

01:35:18.610 --> 01:35:21.920
that had come before, including
the Preserving EXE Summit hosted

01:35:21.920 --> 01:35:23.740
at the LOC in 2013.

01:35:23.740 --> 01:35:26.240
SPIN believes that software
is important to preserve

01:35:26.240 --> 01:35:28.480
because it is information
in and of itself,

01:35:28.480 --> 01:35:32.540
as well as a dependency to
access other digital objects.

01:35:32.540 --> 01:35:36.880
So the common agenda or mission
that unites SPIN's participants

01:35:36.880 --> 01:35:38.810
and supporters is
to preserve software

01:35:38.810 --> 01:35:41.780
through community engagement,
infrastructure support

01:35:41.780 --> 01:35:44.090
and knowledge generation.

01:35:44.090 --> 01:35:45.980
SPIN defines software
preservation

01:35:45.980 --> 01:35:47.340
at the network level

01:35:47.340 --> 01:35:50.540
as basically five core
activity areas necessary

01:35:50.540 --> 01:35:53.290
for successful software
preservation.

01:35:53.290 --> 01:35:56.310
So the first of these
is research,

01:35:56.310 --> 01:35:57.610
so the research working group

01:35:57.610 --> 01:36:00.740
in SPIN is currently creating
a toolkit that people can use

01:36:00.740 --> 01:36:03.520
to gather data about software
preservation and curation,

01:36:03.520 --> 01:36:06.850
upstream, downstream, that's
all in the scope here,

01:36:06.850 --> 01:36:08.650
in their local communities.

01:36:08.650 --> 01:36:11.280
These shared measurements
and associated data establish

01:36:11.280 --> 01:36:12.940
and understanding of
the problems faced

01:36:12.940 --> 01:36:15.020
as it shifts over time.

01:36:15.020 --> 01:36:17.440
The training and
education group is working

01:36:17.440 --> 01:36:19.250
on two major initiatives,
the translation

01:36:19.250 --> 01:36:20.790
of their peer working
group's findings

01:36:20.790 --> 01:36:24.060
into educational materials,
as well as a series

01:36:24.060 --> 01:36:26.440
of software curation
recommendations and guidelines

01:36:26.440 --> 01:36:29.910
for data curators and data
management professionals.

01:36:29.910 --> 01:36:32.080
The metadata and
standards group sent

01:36:32.080 --> 01:36:34.440
out a survey earlier this
year to provide a baseline

01:36:34.440 --> 01:36:35.980
of metadata being
used to describe

01:36:35.980 --> 01:36:38.820
and manage the preservation
of an access to software,

01:36:38.820 --> 01:36:41.210
and based on those findings
even in institutions

01:36:41.210 --> 01:36:43.830
that actively collect software
with policies and agreements

01:36:43.830 --> 01:36:45.650
in place they're
still struggling

01:36:45.650 --> 01:36:48.070
with issues pertaining to
standards, best practice

01:36:48.070 --> 01:36:50.760
and preservation workflows.

01:36:50.760 --> 01:36:53.780
The legal policy group is
focused on legal research

01:36:53.780 --> 01:36:57.040
and advocacy pertaining to
copyright and licensing,

01:36:57.040 --> 01:36:59.810
so this includes the
various best practices,

01:36:59.810 --> 01:37:02.080
work that Euan mentioned
earlier that Brendan

01:37:02.080 --> 01:37:05.790
and Peter are very
actively pursuing.

01:37:05.790 --> 01:37:09.580
This also includes the 1201
exemption, so SPIN has partnered

01:37:09.580 --> 01:37:12.380
for the last two or so years
with the Cyber Law Clinic

01:37:12.380 --> 01:37:14.340
at the Brookman's Client
Center for Internet

01:37:14.340 --> 01:37:15.640
and Society at Harvard.

01:37:15.640 --> 01:37:20.360
And then on 2018, in 2018
we're looking to expand

01:37:20.360 --> 01:37:22.990
to a comparative legal study
that looks at similar approaches

01:37:22.990 --> 01:37:25.190
in two different
national contexts.

01:37:25.190 --> 01:37:29.090
The technological infrastructure
working group is starting their

01:37:29.090 --> 01:37:30.970
data gathering at
the consortial level,

01:37:30.970 --> 01:37:33.170
this is digital preservation
consortial level,

01:37:33.170 --> 01:37:35.320
to understand what existing
digital infrastructure

01:37:35.320 --> 01:37:37.670
organizations already
have in place

01:37:37.670 --> 01:37:41.400
to support storage preservation
access and sharing of software

01:37:41.400 --> 01:37:43.280
and metadata associated
with software.

01:37:43.280 --> 01:37:46.520
And then the communication
working group

01:37:46.520 --> 01:37:49.570
and the governance working
group are all doing the work

01:37:49.570 --> 01:37:53.380
to support those other
five core activity areas.

01:37:53.380 --> 01:37:55.970
We also have affiliated
projects.

01:37:55.970 --> 01:38:00.390
There are currently two
already funded and underway

01:38:00.390 --> 01:38:02.250
that are focusing on areas

01:38:02.250 --> 01:38:05.100
that we feel are really
important with one in tow.

01:38:05.100 --> 01:38:08.140
So those areas would be
broadening participation

01:38:08.140 --> 01:38:11.290
in this work, establishing
the various best practices

01:38:11.290 --> 01:38:16.250
for software preservation, and
scaling access to emulation.

01:38:16.250 --> 01:38:20.510
This is a mostly up-to-date
list of organizations, projects

01:38:20.510 --> 01:38:21.810
and programs represented

01:38:21.810 --> 01:38:23.840
in SPIN's membership
and activities.

01:38:23.840 --> 01:38:28.060
As you can see, a lot
of these or if not all

01:38:28.060 --> 01:38:32.120
of these are cultural memory
institutions of some sort.

01:38:32.120 --> 01:38:35.240
We do have a couple
of different firms

01:38:35.240 --> 01:38:37.360
and we have Software
Heritage, which is focused

01:38:37.360 --> 01:38:41.310
on source codes, specifically
research source code.

01:38:41.310 --> 01:38:43.460
So we have some variation
and we're working

01:38:43.460 --> 01:38:45.380
on that representation.

01:38:45.380 --> 01:38:48.980
So partner with the
Software Preservation Network

01:38:48.980 --> 01:38:52.510
and let's save software
together.

