01:41:37.580 --> 01:41:40.190
a couple others out there.

01:41:40.190 --> 01:41:44.120
And then the Nordic countries
have a Nordic chapter

01:41:44.120 --> 01:41:46.130
that is also broken down
into one for each country.

01:41:46.130 --> 01:41:49.110
But the idea is is that
we see a perspective

01:41:49.110 --> 01:41:52.480
of the building industry
across the entire globe.

01:41:52.480 --> 01:41:54.480
And this is one of the
things I want to emphasize

01:41:54.480 --> 01:41:57.800
in this talk is dealing
with an expanded context.

01:41:57.800 --> 01:42:02.070
I think a lot of times when
we get together in symposiums

01:42:02.070 --> 01:42:06.160
like this and talks about this
we really sort of hyper focus

01:42:06.160 --> 01:42:09.150
on an immediate market
or immediate problem.

01:42:09.150 --> 01:42:12.320
And what we hope to do with
buildingSMART is to get people

01:42:12.320 --> 01:42:15.070
to understand that there
is a larger context,

01:42:15.070 --> 01:42:18.930
that this is a problem lots
of people face in many parts

01:42:18.930 --> 01:42:21.390
of the world, if not
all parts of the world,

01:42:21.390 --> 01:42:26.230
crossing multiple languages
and cultures and practices.

01:42:26.230 --> 01:42:30.290
And so that input is necessary
in order to create standards

01:42:30.290 --> 01:42:33.050
that work well for everybody
or at least baselines

01:42:33.050 --> 01:42:35.100
in which everybody
can built upon.

01:42:35.100 --> 01:42:37.890
And there are a number of people
that are involved that belong

01:42:37.890 --> 01:42:41.820
to this organization
to run the organization

01:42:41.820 --> 01:42:48.820
and promote these ideals and
to develop the standards.

01:42:48.820 --> 01:42:50.880
And the three core programs
we work on are things

01:42:50.880 --> 01:42:53.000
like standards, users
and compliance.

01:42:53.000 --> 01:42:54.770
By standards that's
developing things we'll see

01:42:54.770 --> 01:42:56.070
in the next slide.

01:42:56.070 --> 01:42:58.230
By users it's an
international user program,

01:42:58.230 --> 01:43:00.020
we're actually engaged
with practitioners,

01:43:00.020 --> 01:43:02.540
we have to bring them to the
table to, A, educate them

01:43:02.540 --> 01:43:05.820
about what the standards are and
why they're useful and then, B,

01:43:05.820 --> 01:43:09.790
how to use those things and, C,
get input back from those people

01:43:09.790 --> 01:43:12.020
to understand what are
the best ways to mature

01:43:12.020 --> 01:43:13.320
and move those forward.

01:43:13.320 --> 01:43:15.850
And then finally
there's compliance.

01:43:15.850 --> 01:43:18.500
Like Phil was talking
about with the CAx Forum,

01:43:18.500 --> 01:43:23.390
we have certification
of software to be able

01:43:23.390 --> 01:43:27.190
to exchange this data using
IFC, which we'll talk about.

01:43:27.190 --> 01:43:29.470
We have that certification
program that does that.

01:43:29.470 --> 01:43:32.380
So in the building industry
there are applications

01:43:32.380 --> 01:43:33.680
that have been certified
to be able

01:43:33.680 --> 01:43:35.540
to exchange information
with each other.

01:43:35.540 --> 01:43:38.550
The challenge is getting
end users to understand that

01:43:38.550 --> 01:43:40.150
and to actually utilize it.

01:43:40.150 --> 01:43:42.920
And then we're also
launching soon a professional

01:43:42.920 --> 01:43:46.100
certification which says,
hey, I not only understand BIM

01:43:46.100 --> 01:43:48.790
but I understand OpenBIM
at a professional level

01:43:48.790 --> 01:43:51.140
as an individual but
also as a business level

01:43:51.140 --> 01:43:53.480
and an organization level.

01:43:53.480 --> 01:43:56.980
So buildingSMART is a
conglomeration of companies

01:43:56.980 --> 01:43:58.560
and organizations that
are putting their money

01:43:58.560 --> 01:43:59.860
where their mouth is.

01:43:59.860 --> 01:44:03.170
At different levels of
support and sponsorship

01:44:03.170 --> 01:44:04.470
in many different parts

01:44:04.470 --> 01:44:08.570
of the world they're saying this
matters to us, we see the value

01:44:08.570 --> 01:44:11.140
of trying to provide
standards for the industry

01:44:11.140 --> 01:44:13.210
across all the different
processes,

01:44:13.210 --> 01:44:16.820
and so we're putting money
in in order to fund all

01:44:16.820 --> 01:44:18.730
of the activities
that are necessary

01:44:18.730 --> 01:44:20.440
for this to move forward.

01:44:20.440 --> 01:44:23.390
And essentially what do we do?

01:44:23.390 --> 01:44:25.500
So simple as this, we develop

01:44:25.500 --> 01:44:27.880
and maintain open
international standards for BIM.

01:44:27.880 --> 01:44:31.660
As I said before, how do we
remove that proprietary layer

01:44:31.660 --> 01:44:33.540
from the exchange of data?

01:44:33.540 --> 01:44:37.610
And there are three main
or three core standards

01:44:37.610 --> 01:44:39.020
that we really deal with.

01:44:39.020 --> 01:44:40.320
Information delivery manual

01:44:40.320 --> 01:44:42.980
which essentially is how do
you establish the business case

01:44:42.980 --> 01:44:47.150
for exchanging data or
storing this data, right?

01:44:47.150 --> 01:44:49.620
Greg was alluding to this
earlier about there has

01:44:49.620 --> 01:44:53.300
to be a business
value, that makes sense.

01:44:53.300 --> 01:44:57.000
So if we can establish what
those business values are then

01:44:57.000 --> 01:45:00.970
we can begin to build the
standards and the technology

01:45:00.970 --> 01:45:03.320
that then support
all of those values.

01:45:03.320 --> 01:45:08.350
The industry foundation classes
is really the technical part

01:45:08.350 --> 01:45:12.020
of our standards, and this is
the technical specification

01:45:12.020 --> 01:45:15.270
or the data model for
that free exchange.

01:45:15.270 --> 01:45:16.800
And then there's the
international framework

01:45:16.800 --> 01:45:19.530
for dictionaries, or as Roger
will talk about this idea

01:45:19.530 --> 01:45:21.920
of the buildingSMART
data dictionary,

01:45:21.920 --> 01:45:26.330
is how then do we cross all
of these cultural and market

01:45:26.330 --> 01:45:29.110
and language lines to
have common understandings

01:45:29.110 --> 01:45:32.930
of what building elements are
and what materials are so that

01:45:32.930 --> 01:45:37.220
when somebody says it in one
language we know immediately

01:45:37.220 --> 01:45:39.630
through translation what it
means in another language.

01:45:39.630 --> 01:45:42.720
And that's no small
thing because we live

01:45:42.720 --> 01:45:47.200
in a global market now, right,
we are in a global industry,

01:45:47.200 --> 01:45:49.570
we get parts from all
other parts of the world.

01:45:49.570 --> 01:45:51.340
We can have designers
from multiple parts

01:45:51.340 --> 01:45:53.000
of the world working together.

01:45:53.000 --> 01:45:56.520
So we have to have those
layers of understanding.

01:45:56.520 --> 01:45:57.870
And it's not just about design,

01:45:57.870 --> 01:46:01.200
this is about the entire
lifecycle of the building.

01:46:01.200 --> 01:46:04.300
In effect a reiterative
lifecycle of the building

01:46:04.300 --> 01:46:06.500
in which when you come
to decommissioning,

01:46:06.500 --> 01:46:08.780
the end of the lifecycle
of a building,

01:46:08.780 --> 01:46:10.080
if we can gather enough data

01:46:10.080 --> 01:46:12.900
about that building's
performance over its lifecycle

01:46:12.900 --> 01:46:15.610
that gives us more
information to then turnaround

01:46:15.610 --> 01:46:18.250
and do a better job
on the next building.

01:46:18.250 --> 01:46:21.520
Or decide what do we do with
all of those old assets,

01:46:21.520 --> 01:46:24.460
can we recycle them, can we
reuse them, if we download them

01:46:24.460 --> 01:46:25.840
where are they going to?

01:46:25.840 --> 01:46:27.140
We can capture a lot

01:46:27.140 --> 01:46:29.570
of information throughout
the entire lifecycle.

01:46:29.570 --> 01:46:32.570
And buildingSMART International

01:46:32.570 --> 01:46:35.570
as an international organization
is a standards organization

01:46:35.570 --> 01:46:38.860
and works through multiple
organizations primarily

01:46:38.860 --> 01:46:41.240
at the top ISO, right?

01:46:41.240 --> 01:46:45.790
This all exists internationally
because of ISO, but we also work

01:46:45.790 --> 01:46:48.210
with other national
standards organizations.

01:46:48.210 --> 01:46:51.250
So, for example, in a regional
sense we deal with CEN,

01:46:51.250 --> 01:46:52.760
which deals with all of Europe,

01:46:52.760 --> 01:46:54.460
but then within CEN
you have things

01:46:54.460 --> 01:46:55.760
like the British standards

01:46:55.760 --> 01:46:57.980
and you have the
German DIN standards.

01:46:57.980 --> 01:46:59.600
And when something is accepted

01:46:59.600 --> 01:47:01.990
at the ISO level it
trickles on down.

01:47:01.990 --> 01:47:04.150
Now we also get things
from ISO in order

01:47:04.150 --> 01:47:08.180
to feed the IFC standard and
step is one of those, step,

01:47:08.180 --> 01:47:12.970
IFC is actually a derivative of
step and we use XML, we use X3D,

01:47:12.970 --> 01:47:15.150
these are all other
ISO standards that feed

01:47:15.150 --> 01:47:18.280
into what we're doing so that
we're not really reinventing the

01:47:18.280 --> 01:47:21.040
wheel, we're using best
practices and best standards

01:47:21.040 --> 01:47:23.870
that are already out there.

01:47:23.870 --> 01:47:25.170
And in the end what
you really need

01:47:25.170 --> 01:47:28.430
to understand is
buildingSMART are people.

01:47:28.430 --> 01:47:30.270
So this is a photo that
was taken just a couple

01:47:30.270 --> 01:47:31.910
of weeks ago in London.

01:47:31.910 --> 01:47:33.210
Greg is in there somewhere.

01:47:33.210 --> 01:47:35.000
Roger is in there somewhere.

01:47:35.000 --> 01:47:38.610
Where we all got together and
we talk about these issues,

01:47:38.610 --> 01:47:42.190
we talk about what are ways
to improve the coverage

01:47:42.190 --> 01:47:43.890
of IFC throughout the
built environment?

01:47:43.890 --> 01:47:47.970
What are the use cases
for exchanging data

01:47:47.970 --> 01:47:50.230
between different stakeholders?

01:47:50.230 --> 01:47:51.530
You know, what are
these projects

01:47:51.530 --> 01:47:53.430
that we can bring together and
make it more useful for people?

01:47:53.430 --> 01:47:56.800
How do we promote it to
the rest of the world?

01:47:56.800 --> 01:47:59.540
Okay, so as I said,
three main standards.

01:47:59.540 --> 01:48:01.200
The one I really want to
talk about today is IFC

01:48:01.200 --> 01:48:03.310
because in this context

01:48:03.310 --> 01:48:06.060
of how do we preserve
information this is the one

01:48:06.060 --> 01:48:07.730
that matters really the most.

01:48:07.730 --> 01:48:12.320
So IFC in its essence
is just a description

01:48:12.320 --> 01:48:17.430
of the built environment
that's open public standard.

01:48:17.430 --> 01:48:21.460
It's nonproprietary, no vendor
owns it, can control it, right?

01:48:21.460 --> 01:48:23.020
It belongs to the world.

01:48:23.020 --> 01:48:24.560
It's free to access.

01:48:24.560 --> 01:48:28.010
And the whole idea is that
in that description it's

01:48:28.010 --> 01:48:30.240
about geometry and
information, not data,

01:48:30.240 --> 01:48:32.800
because the data side just
once told me he says data is

01:48:32.800 --> 01:48:35.660
for computers, information
is for people.

01:48:35.660 --> 01:48:38.380
It's context, it's semantics.

01:48:38.380 --> 01:48:42.630
So if I look at an example of
a piece of geometry I can look

01:48:42.630 --> 01:48:44.110
at it and say, well, what is it?

01:48:44.110 --> 01:48:45.610
This means nothing, it looks

01:48:45.610 --> 01:48:48.400
like something, but
I could guess.

01:48:48.400 --> 01:48:51.830
And what IFC does is it has data
structures in there that says,

01:48:51.830 --> 01:48:56.420
okay, well, as geometry is this
a solid or is it a surface,

01:48:56.420 --> 01:48:59.460
you know, what level of
complexity of it is there?

01:48:59.460 --> 01:49:02.260
What is it, what is
it in relationship

01:49:02.260 --> 01:49:04.090
to how we think of buildings?

01:49:04.090 --> 01:49:07.590
Is it a column, is it
a duct, is it a pile,

01:49:07.590 --> 01:49:09.730
is it a piece of a wall, right?

01:49:09.730 --> 01:49:11.030
And then what are
the attributes,

01:49:11.030 --> 01:49:13.120
what are the properties to
it, how do I identify it?

01:49:13.120 --> 01:49:15.360
What are its physical
attributes?

01:49:15.360 --> 01:49:19.340
What is its performance
values, and how do we use

01:49:19.340 --> 01:49:23.270
or how do we classify it in
terms of these other systems

01:49:23.270 --> 01:49:29.280
when we do the costing
or mapping to systems

01:49:29.280 --> 01:49:33.140
for tracking processes, right?

01:49:33.140 --> 01:49:35.180
And then what are
the relationships?

01:49:35.180 --> 01:49:37.400
When then I can see, I can
determine is something external

01:49:37.400 --> 01:49:38.700
to the building or
internal to the building.

01:49:38.700 --> 01:49:41.670
Is it being supported by or is
it supporting something else?

01:49:41.670 --> 01:49:42.970
Is it within a particular room?

01:49:42.970 --> 01:49:44.950
Is it within a particular wall?

01:49:44.950 --> 01:49:47.500
So then I can say, hey,
this particular piece

01:49:47.500 --> 01:49:50.720
of geometry has all of
this data attached to it,

01:49:50.720 --> 01:49:53.700
it has an understanding of
what it is and I can query it

01:49:53.700 --> 01:49:55.650
and I can look at it and
I can get a better sense

01:49:55.650 --> 01:49:58.730
of what's going on
and what it is.

01:49:58.730 --> 01:50:03.220
But it even stretches out to
understand the built environment

01:50:03.220 --> 01:50:05.110
as we understand the
built environment.

01:50:05.110 --> 01:50:07.320
There's a project level,
there's the site level,

01:50:07.320 --> 01:50:09.320
there's the building level,
and then there's all the pieces

01:50:09.320 --> 01:50:10.690
that become a part of it.

01:50:10.690 --> 01:50:13.870
And it's not just about objects,
but it's also about this idea

01:50:13.870 --> 01:50:18.320
of controls, of performance
history, of processes,

01:50:18.320 --> 01:50:21.430
of the people that are
actually assigned or a part

01:50:21.430 --> 01:50:25.290
of these objects
and these processes.

01:50:25.290 --> 01:50:26.670
And it's more than
just buildings now.

01:50:26.670 --> 01:50:28.370
We're currently in a
phase where we're looking

01:50:28.370 --> 01:50:30.970
at describing the
entire built environment.

01:50:30.970 --> 01:50:34.400
Infrastructure is now being
worked on by multiple countries,

01:50:34.400 --> 01:50:38.730
describing roads, bridges,
railways, tunneling.

01:50:38.730 --> 01:50:41.610
We're not going to
stop at buildings.

01:50:41.610 --> 01:50:43.460
And this has been
going on for some time,

01:50:43.460 --> 01:50:47.730
so over 21 years,
31 years, oh, jeez.

01:50:47.730 --> 01:50:52.370
And it began with an alliance
with Autodesk and trying

01:50:52.370 --> 01:50:53.900
to determine how
do they get data

01:50:53.900 --> 01:50:56.540
between all these different
permutations of the platform

01:50:56.540 --> 01:50:58.490
and has turned into
something greater than that

01:50:58.490 --> 01:51:00.650
and involves a lot of
different people and a lot

01:51:00.650 --> 01:51:03.350
of different applications.

01:51:03.350 --> 01:51:05.850
IFC can be expressed
in multiple ways.

01:51:05.850 --> 01:51:07.550
We're talking about
the step file,

01:51:07.550 --> 01:51:10.670
but there's also using
computer science best practices

01:51:10.670 --> 01:51:14.710
as being able to exchange this
information using XML formats.

01:51:14.710 --> 01:51:17.270
And being able to zip these
things up into containers

01:51:17.270 --> 01:51:19.810
that can be exchanged
more efficiently.

01:51:19.810 --> 01:51:21.630
But the future is
looking even better.

01:51:21.630 --> 01:51:23.290
It's really amazing as we look

01:51:23.290 --> 01:51:25.330
at what computer science
has done over the last 10

01:51:25.330 --> 01:51:27.190
to 15 years, how can we apply

01:51:27.190 --> 01:51:29.810
that to what we're trying
to do with our data?

01:51:29.810 --> 01:51:32.020
When can we get to the point
where we're no longer talking

01:51:32.020 --> 01:51:33.890
about file exchange,
but we're simply talking

01:51:33.890 --> 01:51:36.490
about querying tool to tool and
we're streaming data around,

01:51:36.490 --> 01:51:40.600
where we're saving all
of it somewhere or linked

01:51:40.600 --> 01:51:42.790
in multiple places
and we're able

01:51:42.790 --> 01:51:45.600
to bring information
together at that point of use

01:51:45.600 --> 01:51:47.220
and the point of need?

01:51:47.220 --> 01:51:49.460
So we're beginning to follow
along what's happening

01:51:49.460 --> 01:51:51.190
in the greater computing
industry

01:51:51.190 --> 01:51:54.160
to really mature the
standard and how we use data.

01:51:54.160 --> 01:51:57.970
And in the end it's the
best way to communicate

01:51:57.970 --> 01:52:00.850
to building data
globally without barriers.

01:52:00.850 --> 01:52:04.070
There's no other option
really out there that gives us

01:52:04.070 --> 01:52:08.140
that ability of determining
semantics and context

01:52:08.140 --> 01:52:12.070
and description and processes.

01:52:12.070 --> 01:52:17.830
And we're doing this because
the software industry globally

01:52:17.830 --> 01:52:19.460
is large.

01:52:19.460 --> 01:52:21.120
I know there's a lot
of talk about vendor A,

01:52:21.120 --> 01:52:24.420
I hear this all the time, right?

01:52:24.420 --> 01:52:27.440
You can imagine how many of
these conferences I go to

01:52:27.440 --> 01:52:30.130
and it's all about this,
it's all about this.

01:52:30.130 --> 01:52:34.210
Yet if I look globally
there are hundreds,

01:52:34.210 --> 01:52:36.110
over a thousand different
software companies

01:52:36.110 --> 01:52:40.820
that serve all of their markets
very well with many users,

01:52:40.820 --> 01:52:43.560
and they all have data that
needs to work together in order

01:52:43.560 --> 01:52:47.470
to accomplish the idea of
designing, procuring, building

01:52:47.470 --> 01:52:50.090
and operating buildings.

01:52:50.090 --> 01:52:51.540
Because if I work on this

01:52:51.540 --> 01:52:55.510
as a tool centric methodology
it requires a lot of work

01:52:55.510 --> 01:52:58.390
for one vendor to connect to
a bunch of different vendors.

01:52:58.390 --> 01:53:01.400
And instead what we need to do
is we need to turn this model

01:53:01.400 --> 01:53:04.530
from being tool centric
into being data centric

01:53:04.530 --> 01:53:06.970
because this is expensive
for a developer

01:53:06.970 --> 01:53:09.570
to do, it's very expensive.

01:53:09.570 --> 01:53:12.200
So if I move the model
from application centric

01:53:12.200 --> 01:53:15.480
to content centric I may do
about the same amount of work

01:53:15.480 --> 01:53:17.380
to get two applications
to talk to each other,

01:53:17.380 --> 01:53:18.680
but when I get beyond

01:53:18.680 --> 01:53:21.490
that one-to-one relationship
it becomes more difficult

01:53:21.490 --> 01:53:23.160
for somebody.

01:53:23.160 --> 01:53:25.420
And if I'm dealing with many
partners that are trying

01:53:25.420 --> 01:53:28.030
to speak to each other there's a
lot of work that has to be done,

01:53:28.030 --> 01:53:29.700
and then lots of
things are broken

01:53:29.700 --> 01:53:32.880
as each individual person
revises their content

01:53:32.880 --> 01:53:34.500
or revises their applications.

01:53:34.500 --> 01:53:36.930
So if we're all working
on establishing

01:53:36.930 --> 01:53:40.530
or supporting a single standard
we all do the same amount

01:53:40.530 --> 01:53:43.800
of work and in the end what
we're doing is were doing less

01:53:43.800 --> 01:53:46.180
work, we're lowering
the threshold for more

01:53:46.180 --> 01:53:49.670
and more people to come
in and utilize that data

01:53:49.670 --> 01:53:51.870
and be valuable to the process

01:53:51.870 --> 01:53:54.760
and we're creating a larger
ecosystem for the end users,

01:53:54.760 --> 01:53:57.880
for the market who want this
data, who want these tools

01:53:57.880 --> 01:54:00.190
to do more and more stuff.

01:54:00.190 --> 01:54:03.190
Because in the end what
happens is if we rely

01:54:03.190 --> 01:54:06.800
on a tool centric model, if
you invest into a platform

01:54:06.800 --> 01:54:09.770
and that platform doesn't
contain certain functionalities

01:54:09.770 --> 01:54:12.310
that are necessary for
your business process

01:54:12.310 --> 01:54:14.390
that means you don't do them.

01:54:14.390 --> 01:54:16.760
Now is that acceptable?

01:54:16.760 --> 01:54:19.440
If you were to say, hey,
you can buy a Ford vehicle,

01:54:19.440 --> 01:54:21.800
but you can't drive on
any of the interstates,

01:54:21.800 --> 01:54:24.470
would that be acceptable?

01:54:24.470 --> 01:54:27.790
So why do we accept that
in the building industry?

01:54:27.790 --> 01:54:31.390
And owners and designers need
to turnaround and force us

01:54:31.390 --> 01:54:33.810
as vendors to say you
need to support this

01:54:33.810 --> 01:54:36.940
because our data is more
important than your tools are.

01:54:36.940 --> 01:54:41.280
So the whole point is this
is about creating value

01:54:41.280 --> 01:54:44.280
in the data, that
you own the data

01:54:44.280 --> 01:54:46.930
when it's open format, right?

01:54:46.930 --> 01:54:49.010
Otherwise you have to have an
explicit agreement with each

01:54:49.010 --> 01:54:51.960
of your vendors and if you stop
paying the vendors you stop

01:54:51.960 --> 01:54:54.460
having access to that data.

01:54:54.460 --> 01:54:58.390
Every owner should hear
that statement and go is

01:54:58.390 --> 01:55:02.890
that acceptable,
is that acceptable?

01:55:02.890 --> 01:55:06.580
If you can't access it 10 years
down the road what was the point

01:55:06.580 --> 01:55:09.770
of even aggregating all
of it in the first place?

01:55:09.770 --> 01:55:12.690
So you have that
ability, it has longevity.

01:55:12.690 --> 01:55:15.030
And as a standard that we
provide we're also providing

01:55:15.030 --> 01:55:16.740
this ability to making
it extensible.

01:55:16.740 --> 01:55:19.770
You can keep building
on that data over time.

01:55:19.770 --> 01:55:21.990
We don't have these radical
changes in the standard

01:55:21.990 --> 01:55:26.920
that says, oh, well, now
like miniCAD 5 I can't open

01:55:26.920 --> 01:55:31.560
in VectorWorks 2019, it's
almost impossible to do.

01:55:31.560 --> 01:55:35.120
But with IFC files, with these
IFC standard I can always build

01:55:35.120 --> 01:55:41.220
tools on top of those old
IFC files and access them.

01:55:41.220 --> 01:55:44.690
So for more information
go to buildingsmart.org,

01:55:44.690 --> 01:55:47.030
there's a technical site
that deals with developers,

01:55:47.030 --> 01:55:49.340
and those who are
interested contact me,

01:55:49.340 --> 01:55:51.510
I'd love to tell you more.

