01:57:22.390 --> 01:57:25.490
So you can find this at the BIM
Standard, but it's pretty good

01:57:25.490 --> 01:57:28.070
for one sentence about
what we're trying to do

01:57:28.070 --> 01:57:33.030
with information across the
lifecycle and functional

01:57:33.030 --> 01:57:35.900
and physical characteristics
of a building.

01:57:35.900 --> 01:57:38.330
So I know we're here to
talk about archiving,

01:57:38.330 --> 01:57:42.410
but I think what Jeff was
referencing was how we use

01:57:42.410 --> 01:57:44.810
standards to organize
information, and I'm going

01:57:44.810 --> 01:57:46.830
to talk about that
aspect of it, too.

01:57:46.830 --> 01:57:50.150
I think of we don't have well
organized information it makes

01:57:50.150 --> 01:57:53.980
the problem of archiving it and
reusing it a lot more difficult.

01:57:53.980 --> 01:57:57.260
So most of our work is really
focused on how do we organize

01:57:57.260 --> 01:58:02.370
and get value out of information
and apply it to solve problems.

01:58:02.370 --> 01:58:05.210
I'm going to go through a couple
slides here real quickly to kind

01:58:05.210 --> 01:58:08.550
of set it up, and then I'm
going to share some use cases

01:58:08.550 --> 01:58:10.770
of projects we've
worked on for agencies

01:58:10.770 --> 01:58:12.900
where they have been
implementing some

01:58:12.900 --> 01:58:14.340
of these concepts.

01:58:14.340 --> 01:58:18.620
And so this is, you know, I just
want to point out that a model

01:58:18.620 --> 01:58:22.260
and IFC gives us a
structured way to do this,

01:58:22.260 --> 01:58:26.640
but the good thing about a
model is it consists of objects

01:58:26.640 --> 01:58:28.290
and those objects
have properties.

01:58:28.290 --> 01:58:31.620
And once you've identified
those things as the key aspect

01:58:31.620 --> 01:58:34.980
of a building you can attach
a lot of other things to them.

01:58:34.980 --> 01:58:37.370
You can structure the
properties in an organized way.

01:58:37.370 --> 01:58:40.130
You can put identifiers on
them that let you find them

01:58:40.130 --> 01:58:42.220
in all kinds of other
applications.

01:58:42.220 --> 01:58:46.420
You can embed specifications
that say more about it

01:58:46.420 --> 01:58:48.810
in language that
people can understand.

01:58:48.810 --> 01:58:50.950
You can connect it to
external information.

01:58:50.950 --> 01:58:52.870
So that's the interesting thing.

01:58:52.870 --> 01:58:55.670
And the model, we spend
a lot of time looking

01:58:55.670 --> 01:58:58.170
at how do you replicate
the graphics that were done

01:58:58.170 --> 01:59:00.130
in all kinds of different
systems?

01:59:00.130 --> 01:59:04.420
But a lot of the value in
using models is in the data

01:59:04.420 --> 01:59:08.250
or the information that
gets attached to them.

01:59:08.250 --> 01:59:12.720
It's not trivial to think
about the information, itself,

01:59:12.720 --> 01:59:15.230
and I've borrowed
this from Kimono Numa,

01:59:15.230 --> 01:59:17.310
who works with us on
a lot of projects.

01:59:17.310 --> 01:59:23.580
And the idea that platforms
and separating information

01:59:23.580 --> 01:59:26.400
from the applications is
critical, and we're sort

01:59:26.400 --> 01:59:28.540
of viewed as being behind
in the building industry

01:59:28.540 --> 01:59:31.570
and I think that's relatively
well accepted in our adoption

01:59:31.570 --> 01:59:34.820
of technology, but we can
look to others like Telcom

01:59:34.820 --> 01:59:37.120
and what they've been
able to do and think

01:59:37.120 --> 01:59:38.470
about how it applies to us.

01:59:38.470 --> 01:59:41.620
You know, inside owner
organizations there's tons

01:59:41.620 --> 01:59:44.870
of valuable information,
but it's in databases

01:59:44.870 --> 01:59:47.590
that were created years
ago, they have structures

01:59:47.590 --> 01:59:50.230
that have gotten a little
out of whack over time.

01:59:50.230 --> 01:59:53.520
But it's still there and
a lot of it is good data

01:59:53.520 --> 01:59:57.060
and if you can reorganize
it, apply some standards

01:59:57.060 --> 01:59:59.080
to it you can make
it a lot more useful.

01:59:59.080 --> 02:00:02.580
The key thing is starting by
separating the information

02:00:02.580 --> 02:00:05.710
from the applications, the key
information that is valuable

02:00:05.710 --> 02:00:07.770
to how you run your business.

02:00:07.770 --> 02:00:09.960
I'm not going to say
too much about this,

02:00:09.960 --> 02:00:14.380
but other than to say
this is a way to be able

02:00:14.380 --> 02:00:17.650
to preserve information if you
have it logically organized.

02:00:17.650 --> 02:00:20.330
And a lot of it is tabular data,

02:00:20.330 --> 02:00:24.060
it's data about the
things that you're doing.

02:00:24.060 --> 02:00:27.090
It's nice to represent it with
models and there's some things

02:00:27.090 --> 02:00:28.800
that you can't do
without a model,

02:00:28.800 --> 02:00:30.850
but a lot of it is
about the data.

02:00:30.850 --> 02:00:34.400
And also in the case of the
Government it's real important

02:00:34.400 --> 02:00:37.920
to use standards because
you can't be proprietary

02:00:37.920 --> 02:00:40.010
about the tools you request.

02:00:40.010 --> 02:00:43.310
So if you have an open
standard you can reference that

02:00:43.310 --> 02:00:45.510
and you can ask for tools
that comply with it,

02:00:45.510 --> 02:00:47.730
and that's really important.

02:00:47.730 --> 02:00:49.820
There's another important
thing on that slide was legacy.

02:00:49.820 --> 02:00:52.970
We're never going to
remake every legacy system

02:00:52.970 --> 02:00:56.670
to follow a standard, but if
it's structured well enough

02:00:56.670 --> 02:01:00.330
that we can map standards
to it then we can share it

02:01:00.330 --> 02:01:03.520
with all the other processes
that are out there that we want

02:01:03.520 --> 02:01:06.580
to connect to and then I
think we can also have a way

02:01:06.580 --> 02:01:11.650
to keep track of it over time.

02:01:11.650 --> 02:01:14.420
We need the information to
be useable, that's important,

02:01:14.420 --> 02:01:18.160
but useable is a lot different
in a lot of different context.

02:01:18.160 --> 02:01:21.520
I mean if I want to say this is
a space what do I need to know

02:01:21.520 --> 02:01:23.200
about it, but if I also want

02:01:23.200 --> 02:01:26.060
to capture the lighting
requirements and the air changes

02:01:26.060 --> 02:01:27.650
and everything in it
we need different kinds

02:01:27.650 --> 02:01:30.940
of information to do that.

02:01:30.940 --> 02:01:33.400
But without the information
we can't make good decisions,

02:01:33.400 --> 02:01:36.810
so we really want to figure out
how do we organize information

02:01:36.810 --> 02:01:39.590
in a way that can support the
decisions that we need to make

02:01:39.590 --> 02:01:44.330
and give us the ability to
make it useful over time,

02:01:44.330 --> 02:01:45.830
not just in one sense.

02:01:45.830 --> 02:01:50.090
And I guess I put this on
here because, I don't know,

02:01:50.090 --> 02:01:51.390
what are we trying to solve?

02:01:51.390 --> 02:01:53.480
Well, at the end of the
day we're really doing this

02:01:53.480 --> 02:01:55.940
because we want to make things
better and more efficient.

02:01:55.940 --> 02:01:58.410
I mean it's fun to talk about
computers and how they work,

02:01:58.410 --> 02:02:03.810
but if we can't lower cost,
if we can't use less resources

02:02:03.810 --> 02:02:06.500
in the environment it probably
doesn't matter all that much.

02:02:06.500 --> 02:02:09.580
And so the Brits are kind
of an interesting study

02:02:09.580 --> 02:02:12.630
because they have one
agency that manages building

02:02:12.630 --> 02:02:16.730
for the whole Government
and they take a macro view

02:02:16.730 --> 02:02:19.790
of how the building industry
supports everything they're

02:02:19.790 --> 02:02:22.610
doing, and they have
set targets,

02:02:22.610 --> 02:02:25.230
they've got this whole
program on level one,

02:02:25.230 --> 02:02:27.430
level two, level three BIM.

02:02:27.430 --> 02:02:29.250
BIM is at the core
of it for them

02:02:29.250 --> 02:02:31.740
to make their processes better,

02:02:31.740 --> 02:02:34.110
and they've actually
upped their targets

02:02:34.110 --> 02:02:37.210
on what they think they
can do to lower cost,

02:02:37.210 --> 02:02:40.590
to make their country more
productive, to reduce emissions.

02:02:40.590 --> 02:02:44.640
So it's just good to keep in
mind why we're doing this stuff.

02:02:44.640 --> 02:02:46.930
I don't have to talk about this
because Jeff did a good job

02:02:46.930 --> 02:02:48.780
of describing the
buildingSMART standards.

02:02:48.780 --> 02:02:52.110
But one thing is to get your
information organized in a way

02:02:52.110 --> 02:02:54.540
that it's logical and
you can access it.

02:02:54.540 --> 02:02:56.350
The next thing is to
apply standards to it

02:02:56.350 --> 02:03:01.270
so others can efficiently
utilize your information.

02:03:01.270 --> 02:03:03.250
It's one thing to
organize it for yourself,

02:03:03.250 --> 02:03:04.550
but it's another
thing to open it

02:03:04.550 --> 02:03:07.290
up so others can
use it efficiently.

02:03:07.290 --> 02:03:08.870
So what we've been
trying to do is look

02:03:08.870 --> 02:03:10.840
at how can we apply
buildingSMART's standards

02:03:10.840 --> 02:03:14.340
in some kind of a process
so that we could replicate.

02:03:14.340 --> 02:03:16.330
And we've been experimenting
with this

02:03:16.330 --> 02:03:17.630
on several projects now.

02:03:17.630 --> 02:03:20.850
Somebody said there's no one
solution and that's really true,

02:03:20.850 --> 02:03:23.920
and you'd have to experiment
to find a good solution.

02:03:23.920 --> 02:03:26.860
But IFC is the best way
to document buildings,

02:03:26.860 --> 02:03:30.390
and there's some
connected processes, IDM.

02:03:30.390 --> 02:03:32.990
It's important to know what
you're trying to accomplish,

02:03:32.990 --> 02:03:36.080
where it fits into the bigger
picture, IDM lets you do

02:03:36.080 --> 02:03:37.880
that by having a process map

02:03:37.880 --> 02:03:40.730
and defining exchanges
of information.

02:03:40.730 --> 02:03:43.210
And then within the realm
of IFC there's a way

02:03:43.210 --> 02:03:46.960
to document those exchanges
so that they can be captured

02:03:46.960 --> 02:03:49.360
in software, and that's really
important because we don't want

02:03:49.360 --> 02:03:51.290
to do this stuff with
pencil and paper.

02:03:51.290 --> 02:03:54.080
We want to automate
it and digitize it.

02:03:54.080 --> 02:03:57.660
And we think it's also, we think
every exchange should have a

02:03:57.660 --> 02:03:59.900
specification that says
what you're trying to do,

02:03:59.900 --> 02:04:01.240
who wants the information,

02:04:01.240 --> 02:04:03.150
who is the sender,
who is the receiver.

02:04:03.150 --> 02:04:05.330
And what is it, if
there's a dictionary,

02:04:05.330 --> 02:04:08.010
a data dictionary associated
with it that tells you

02:04:08.010 --> 02:04:10.580
in multiple languages, because
this stuff is being used

02:04:10.580 --> 02:04:14.690
and reused all over the
world, what's in that exchange

02:04:14.690 --> 02:04:17.320
and then you can put
that into applications.

02:04:17.320 --> 02:04:21.920
And we can do a better job of
standardizing these processes.

02:04:21.920 --> 02:04:24.550
I guess Greg said,
what's the business case?

02:04:24.550 --> 02:04:26.720
Well, the business
case is we have

02:04:26.720 --> 02:04:29.320
to invest a little more
upfront to save a little more

02:04:29.320 --> 02:04:31.990
on the backend, and that's
really in the owner's realm.

02:04:31.990 --> 02:04:35.270
So I think where a lot
of the opportunity comes

02:04:35.270 --> 02:04:38.680
to push this forward is for
owners and they're the ones

02:04:38.680 --> 02:04:42.660
who also need to archive this
information about these assets.

02:04:42.660 --> 02:04:44.480
So the first use
case I want to talk

02:04:44.480 --> 02:04:47.900
about is some work we
did for Federal Highway.

02:04:47.900 --> 02:04:50.560
They were trying to say how
can we have a standard for how

02:04:50.560 --> 02:04:53.310
to get digital models
of bridges, you know,

02:04:53.310 --> 02:04:55.920
every piece of infrastructure
in the contract?

02:04:55.920 --> 02:04:59.080
You deliver a drawing that
says the requirements on it,

02:04:59.080 --> 02:05:01.430
but if we want to move to
modeling we need a way to do

02:05:01.430 --> 02:05:04.480
that that is standardized,
that can be replicated,

02:05:04.480 --> 02:05:08.320
that's not based on one
vendor's software solution.

02:05:08.320 --> 02:05:10.030
And so they were
looking at options.

02:05:10.030 --> 02:05:14.180
We explored using the IFC,
the buildingSMART tools

02:05:14.180 --> 02:05:16.260
as the foundation for this.

02:05:16.260 --> 02:05:19.660
We developed an IDM that for
the entire bridge construction

02:05:19.660 --> 02:05:22.600
process we focused on
one of the exchanges,

02:05:22.600 --> 02:05:24.420
designed to construction.

02:05:24.420 --> 02:05:26.800
We, importantly, took
some real examples

02:05:26.800 --> 02:05:28.710
and actually modeled them

02:05:28.710 --> 02:05:31.580
and developed the
requirements from real examples.

02:05:31.580 --> 02:05:33.590
So really it's important
to begin at the end

02:05:33.590 --> 02:05:34.890
and work your way backwards,

02:05:34.890 --> 02:05:37.270
and that's what this project
gave us the ability to do.

02:05:37.270 --> 02:05:39.830
We were able to develop
a process map

02:05:39.830 --> 02:05:41.580
and the exchange specification.

02:05:41.580 --> 02:05:46.580
We worked with Georgia Tech,
we worked with a specialist

02:05:46.580 --> 02:05:49.470
in modeling and within IFC.

02:05:49.470 --> 02:05:52.000
And now this project is
continuing to move forward.

02:05:52.000 --> 02:05:54.730
AASHTO is picking
up the development

02:05:54.730 --> 02:05:56.030
of a national standard,

02:05:56.030 --> 02:05:58.750
they have projects
going now in this realm.

02:05:58.750 --> 02:06:01.540
So we're talking a lot
about documenting buildings,

02:06:01.540 --> 02:06:04.910
but documenting infrastructure
is really important

02:06:04.910 --> 02:06:07.910
if we're going to add all
kinds of services on top of it.

02:06:07.910 --> 02:06:10.990
And one interesting thing in
the infrastructure market,

02:06:10.990 --> 02:06:14.840
there's 50 owners of our
infrastructure assets

02:06:14.840 --> 02:06:18.850
in this country, there's
not 50,000 like there are

02:06:18.850 --> 02:06:20.690
for buildings or
500,000 or whatever.

02:06:20.690 --> 02:06:23.490
So they have some power to
consolidate what's going on.

02:06:23.490 --> 02:06:25.410
And there's a lot
happening worldwide in this,

02:06:25.410 --> 02:06:28.020
so there's a lot
they're borrowing from.

02:06:28.020 --> 02:06:31.300
So in the building realm
we only have process,

02:06:31.300 --> 02:06:33.600
we don't have a process
map for buildings

02:06:33.600 --> 02:06:36.180
but the buildingSMART
alliance is working on it.

02:06:36.180 --> 02:06:38.620
So I just put this in here,
I don't have time to talk

02:06:38.620 --> 02:06:41.800
about it, but we need to be
able to know what's the process

02:06:41.800 --> 02:06:43.490
and what are the exchanges.

02:06:43.490 --> 02:06:47.350
And inside of a process are
these uses, and it's important

02:06:47.350 --> 02:06:51.710
to also define the
uses that you want

02:06:51.710 --> 02:06:55.200
to have processes to support.

02:06:55.200 --> 02:06:58.550
So these were developed by,
identified by Penn State --

02:06:58.550 --> 02:07:00.120
put them on this slide.

02:07:00.120 --> 02:07:03.640
And so this is another
project for Defense Health

02:07:03.640 --> 02:07:06.890
in the Veteran and VA to take --

02:07:06.890 --> 02:07:08.720
space management is
very important for them

02:07:08.720 --> 02:07:12.080
and equipment management in
their facilities so they need

02:07:12.080 --> 02:07:15.650
to identify the spaces and
what equipment goes into them.

02:07:15.650 --> 02:07:17.930
This was all in PDF documents.

02:07:17.930 --> 02:07:22.040
We worked with them with
Anuma to convert this to data,

02:07:22.040 --> 02:07:25.690
take all the information out of
the PDFs, put it into databases,

02:07:25.690 --> 02:07:30.970
and also expose it
to their consultants

02:07:30.970 --> 02:07:34.300
so they could get access to the
requirements from a web service.

02:07:34.300 --> 02:07:37.960
It's all posted on max.gov,
and this tool you can look

02:07:37.960 --> 02:07:40.650
at it online helps you to
organize that information

02:07:40.650 --> 02:07:43.140
and parse it out so it
can be put into models.

02:07:43.140 --> 02:07:48.450
It's got an equipment database
connected to it, as well.

02:07:48.450 --> 02:07:50.470
I'm kind of giving you
a quick overview here

02:07:50.470 --> 02:07:52.680
because I'm going
to run out of time.

02:07:52.680 --> 02:07:54.350
But we're also working
on projects

02:07:54.350 --> 02:07:56.260
for the Department of State.

02:07:56.260 --> 02:07:57.740
They have an interesting
challenge,

02:07:57.740 --> 02:08:02.740
they have a worldwide portfolio
of like over 12,000 assets

02:08:02.740 --> 02:08:04.840
and missions in multiple
countries

02:08:04.840 --> 02:08:06.940
that speak multiple languages,

02:08:06.940 --> 02:08:09.380
and they have an
ongoing building program,

02:08:09.380 --> 02:08:11.680
so how do they organize
all of that?

02:08:11.680 --> 02:08:14.330
So we've focused on
several of these use cases

02:08:14.330 --> 02:08:15.630
as a starting point,

02:08:15.630 --> 02:08:18.780
in particular space planning
is real important to them,

02:08:18.780 --> 02:08:22.270
and we started to look at
how they do space measurement

02:08:22.270 --> 02:08:25.650
and there's a number of
different ways to measure space.

02:08:25.650 --> 02:08:28.630
And so you see that when
you look at the results

02:08:28.630 --> 02:08:31.320
in different systems and
there's also a number

02:08:31.320 --> 02:08:32.780
of different ways you
might name things.

02:08:32.780 --> 02:08:36.520
And all of our organizations
over time, you know, we develop,

02:08:36.520 --> 02:08:38.080
we get different
names for things,

02:08:38.080 --> 02:08:40.360
and actually naming
is real important

02:08:40.360 --> 02:08:44.180
as a fundamental starting point,
but just having it consistent

02:08:44.180 --> 02:08:46.120
in a way that you can --
and put it in someplace

02:08:46.120 --> 02:08:48.660
that you can say this
is the source of truth

02:08:48.660 --> 02:08:50.820
and then you can point the
rest of your organization to it

02:08:50.820 --> 02:08:52.120
and you can start
to build on it.

02:08:52.120 --> 02:08:55.240
So this is really the
starting point, and we've gone

02:08:55.240 --> 02:08:57.300
through this by looking
first at, you know,

02:08:57.300 --> 02:08:59.690
to get space organized we've
gone through this process,

02:08:59.690 --> 02:09:03.020
look at coordinated, the
standards and the guides

02:09:03.020 --> 02:09:05.840
about the information, look

02:09:05.840 --> 02:09:08.820
at now we'll apply industry
standards, we'll continue

02:09:08.820 --> 02:09:12.250
to do that, but first let's
get the information organized.

02:09:12.250 --> 02:09:14.450
It's then developed
ways to communicate

02:09:14.450 --> 02:09:19.010
out to your consultants so that
comes in through execution plans

02:09:19.010 --> 02:09:23.870
and documents that
your contract documents

02:09:23.870 --> 02:09:25.680
and those need to be updated.

02:09:25.680 --> 02:09:28.370
And we also want to move,
and Jeff mentioned this,

02:09:28.370 --> 02:09:29.930
to being able to validate.

02:09:29.930 --> 02:09:31.310
Having a specification

02:09:31.310 --> 02:09:35.140
for information let's you
automate the validation process,

02:09:35.140 --> 02:09:38.230
and I think the whole area
of design review is one

02:09:38.230 --> 02:09:42.050
that we need to continue to
evolve to move away from,

02:09:42.050 --> 02:09:44.370
to move to its much
automated designer view

02:09:44.370 --> 02:09:46.030
as we possibly can.

02:09:46.030 --> 02:09:47.330
Of course, we need
to train people,

02:09:47.330 --> 02:09:52.320
but the end result is we can
rationalize what we call things

02:09:52.320 --> 02:09:55.450
and how we measure things
and communicate that

02:09:55.450 --> 02:09:58.290
and have it work a
lot more efficiently.

02:09:58.290 --> 02:10:00.820
I'm not going to talk
about COBie at all,

02:10:00.820 --> 02:10:04.010
but COBie is an excellent way.

02:10:04.010 --> 02:10:06.590
It uses IFC, it's widely used,

02:10:06.590 --> 02:10:08.670
it's a way to organize
information.

02:10:08.670 --> 02:10:12.300
But I do want to spend a little
time just sharing with you

02:10:12.300 --> 02:10:14.580
about a use case we've
worked on for GSA.

02:10:14.580 --> 02:10:18.430
GSA has been working
on BIM for a long time

02:10:18.430 --> 02:10:20.330
and how to implement it.

02:10:20.330 --> 02:10:21.630
They've got a lot of guides,

02:10:21.630 --> 02:10:25.450
they did the first information
exchange specification

02:10:25.450 --> 02:10:29.480
for spatial program
validation that's been in use.

02:10:29.480 --> 02:10:31.130
And we've been recently
working with them

02:10:31.130 --> 02:10:35.410
to move this concept further
along, and we've been working

02:10:35.410 --> 02:10:37.220
on a use case for
energy analysis

02:10:37.220 --> 02:10:42.900
to say our buildings use energy,
we have baseline standards,

02:10:42.900 --> 02:10:47.840
we have modeling of energy and
design, energy uses and design.

02:10:47.840 --> 02:10:49.880
And then when the building
is operated we have actual

02:10:49.880 --> 02:10:51.180
energy usage.

02:10:51.180 --> 02:10:54.260
But all that stuff is relating
back to the same systems,

02:10:54.260 --> 02:10:58.610
and so if we can put together
a model to evaluate that,

02:10:58.610 --> 02:11:01.550
that could be valuable for
operating the building.

02:11:01.550 --> 02:11:03.840
So we did a process
model of this.

02:11:03.840 --> 02:11:10.690
We took an 8-story real building
that had lots of systems in it

02:11:10.690 --> 02:11:14.420
and we used that
as a case study.

02:11:14.420 --> 02:11:19.170
Then we mapped the ASHRAE
90.1 as the baseline standard,

02:11:19.170 --> 02:11:22.750
EnergyPlus for building,
for doing the modeling,

02:11:22.750 --> 02:11:27.010
and Project Haystack
for the controls data,

02:11:27.010 --> 02:11:29.610
and we mapped all that to IFC.

02:11:29.610 --> 02:11:33.210
So now there's a specification
for how a model needs

02:11:33.210 --> 02:11:36.850
to be configured to
provide, there will be,

02:11:36.850 --> 02:11:40.600
for how to provide the data
for doing analysis and also

02:11:40.600 --> 02:11:42.910
for measuring once the
building has been put

02:11:42.910 --> 02:11:45.520
into operation, the meter data.

02:11:45.520 --> 02:11:51.080
So GSA plans to share the
specification for this

02:11:51.080 --> 02:11:53.400
at some point once the
project is completed,

02:11:53.400 --> 02:11:55.860
and I think it'll be
an interesting thing

02:11:55.860 --> 02:11:57.430
that can be reused.

02:11:57.430 --> 02:12:00.510
I know I'm almost out of time, I
know I'm virtually out of time,

02:12:00.510 --> 02:12:03.060
but I'm going to just do a
couple more quick things.

02:12:03.060 --> 02:12:05.060
So that I really talked about.

02:12:05.060 --> 02:12:09.260
And this idea of having
a process is important,

02:12:09.260 --> 02:12:11.810
and I think this is something
that needs to continue

02:12:11.810 --> 02:12:15.370
to evolve, but how do we define
requirements, how do we publish,

02:12:15.370 --> 02:12:19.130
extend and implement it in
software and then validate it.

02:12:19.130 --> 02:12:23.760
So this is what we're
basing these projects on.

02:12:23.760 --> 02:12:25.770
And the other important
thing is having a place

02:12:25.770 --> 02:12:28.290
to archive information
that you've produced

02:12:28.290 --> 02:12:30.250
so it can be accessed by others.

02:12:30.250 --> 02:12:33.360
And so at NIBS we have
the National BIM Standard,

02:12:33.360 --> 02:12:36.860
which holds the COBie
exchange and other exchanges,

02:12:36.860 --> 02:12:38.160
and these things we're working

02:12:38.160 --> 02:12:41.010
on for agencies will
ultimately end up there

02:12:41.010 --> 02:12:43.440
so that we can use the
reference standards,

02:12:43.440 --> 02:12:45.860
use national standards
and publish this stuff

02:12:45.860 --> 02:12:48.610
and make it available
for industry to use.

02:12:48.610 --> 02:12:51.990
And the process that's
documented there is really good

02:12:51.990 --> 02:12:54.670
for how do you develop
information exchanges

02:12:54.670 --> 02:12:57.660
and make those useful.

02:12:57.660 --> 02:13:00.060
We're kind of at a phase
where we're moving out now

02:13:00.060 --> 02:13:03.030
to implement this in software,
so we're going to find

02:13:03.030 --> 02:13:08.440
out how this works with
GSA's activities fully.

02:13:08.440 --> 02:13:12.830
