02:21:35.120 --> 02:21:37.100
that includes the same
underlying standards.

02:21:37.100 --> 02:21:40.140
So there's that, but the
standards is a future forwards

02:21:40.140 --> 02:21:42.810
approach, while at the same
time librarians, archivists,

02:21:42.810 --> 02:21:45.740
digital preservationists,
researchers that are looking

02:21:45.740 --> 02:21:49.200
at recent history the
last 30, 40, 50 years

02:21:49.200 --> 02:21:52.570
or so are still contending
with what we do

02:21:52.570 --> 02:21:54.660
with everything that
we already have.

02:21:54.660 --> 02:21:58.840
So if we look at collecting
repositories we've invested

02:21:58.840 --> 02:22:03.420
since the latter part of since
the '80s I would guess even

02:22:03.420 --> 02:22:06.640
earlier maybe, we have things
coming in from the '70s,

02:22:06.640 --> 02:22:10.960
we've already been collecting
passively digital objects

02:22:10.960 --> 02:22:13.200
and proprietary file formats.

02:22:13.200 --> 02:22:15.120
They're embedded
in our collections

02:22:15.120 --> 02:22:18.330
and we don't process collections
in archival repositories

02:22:18.330 --> 02:22:22.550
at an item level, we bring
them in in an aggregate level

02:22:22.550 --> 02:22:25.880
and we describe them
at an aggregate level.

02:22:25.880 --> 02:22:29.360
And so what we're finding is
that as researchers come in

02:22:29.360 --> 02:22:34.290
and they have these use
cases for access we're faced

02:22:34.290 --> 02:22:36.920
with this issue of how do we --

02:22:36.920 --> 02:22:39.560
we've already invested
all this time, expertise,

02:22:39.560 --> 02:22:42.790
storage resources to go back to
some of Tim's earlier questions

02:22:42.790 --> 02:22:46.530
around these digital objects
and they take time to process.

02:22:46.530 --> 02:22:49.660
And then we come to the
point of processing them both

02:22:49.660 --> 02:22:52.390
for identifying their
historical and cultural value,

02:22:52.390 --> 02:22:56.240
what we would call appraisal, as
well as providing access to them

02:22:56.240 --> 02:22:58.650
in a reading room
scenario or in sort

02:22:58.650 --> 02:23:01.090
of a private network
scenario based

02:23:01.090 --> 02:23:02.950
on something like university ID.

02:23:02.950 --> 02:23:04.920
So we're sort of looking

02:23:04.920 --> 02:23:08.180
at the stuff we already
have primarily right now.

02:23:08.180 --> 02:23:10.540
And then what I would say
is the future forward part

02:23:10.540 --> 02:23:12.560
of what we do, sort of focused

02:23:12.560 --> 02:23:14.700
in cultural memory
broadly defined,

02:23:14.700 --> 02:23:18.770
which includes higher
ed, would be scientific

02:23:18.770 --> 02:23:21.070
and social scientific
reproducibility.

02:23:21.070 --> 02:23:25.570
And so this is also a standards
future forward facing approach

02:23:25.570 --> 02:23:28.260
which you have things like
the Software Sustainability

02:23:28.260 --> 02:23:31.410
Institute in the UK that's
doing things like helping

02:23:31.410 --> 02:23:34.350
to create recommendations
and standards for how

02:23:34.350 --> 02:23:36.380
to write better research
software.

02:23:36.380 --> 02:23:38.660
But even then, so
you're using some

02:23:38.660 --> 02:23:40.120
of the same underlying
libraries,

02:23:40.120 --> 02:23:42.560
but you're creating
a unique object.

02:23:42.560 --> 02:23:44.900
Another place that
standards sort of plugs

02:23:44.900 --> 02:23:47.390
into the Software
Preservation Network of all

02:23:47.390 --> 02:23:50.550
of these different organizations
that fit into the network

02:23:50.550 --> 02:23:52.550
in different ways, they
have different roles.

02:23:52.550 --> 02:23:56.510
So some organizations, in
fact, NIST has a software,

02:23:56.510 --> 02:23:58.870
the national software
reference library that's used

02:23:58.870 --> 02:24:03.280
as a data corpus just
based on its hash values,

02:24:03.280 --> 02:24:06.000
but it is actually
a software library.

02:24:06.000 --> 02:24:07.930
And so you have these
known collections

02:24:07.930 --> 02:24:09.230
of historical software.

02:24:09.230 --> 02:24:10.530
The internet archive,

02:24:10.530 --> 02:24:13.120
the national software reference
library, Yale University library

02:24:13.120 --> 02:24:16.490
and special collections,
the Computer History Museum.

02:24:16.490 --> 02:24:18.740
And so if we think
about the fact

02:24:18.740 --> 02:24:21.400
that no one institution
is ever going to be able

02:24:21.400 --> 02:24:23.390
to have all the software
they need

02:24:23.390 --> 02:24:26.920
to accommodate the use
cases of their end users

02:24:26.920 --> 02:24:29.150
for the complex digital
objects that they have

02:24:29.150 --> 02:24:32.650
in their collections, we also
are having the same conversation

02:24:32.650 --> 02:24:34.980
around standardization.

02:24:34.980 --> 02:24:38.300
It's just a different
set of stakeholders.

