02:26:44.760 --> 02:26:49.220
the architects, the engineers,
the people in aerospace

02:26:49.220 --> 02:26:53.230
and automotive, who are actually
creating all these objects

02:26:53.230 --> 02:26:56.070
to begin with, I think
we heard a couple things.

02:26:56.070 --> 02:26:58.370
One that I think
we could all agree

02:26:58.370 --> 02:27:00.470
with in our respective
domains is

02:27:00.470 --> 02:27:02.930
that standards are not
so easy to implement.

02:27:02.930 --> 02:27:06.040
There's a lot of
work being done.

02:27:06.040 --> 02:27:08.130
You know, the buildingSMART
initiative is amazing,

02:27:08.130 --> 02:27:10.470
same with the CAx
Implementor Forum.

02:27:10.470 --> 02:27:13.130
You see the amount of
resources, both people's time,

02:27:13.130 --> 02:27:16.890
people's money, organizational
support by software vendors

02:27:16.890 --> 02:27:19.790
and institutions that goes
into making these standards

02:27:19.790 --> 02:27:22.010
to begin with, and then they
have to get implemented.

02:27:22.010 --> 02:27:26.400
And, like Greg said,
these standards need

02:27:26.400 --> 02:27:27.940
to be market based
or the motivation

02:27:27.940 --> 02:27:30.200
for using the standards
has to be market based.

02:27:30.200 --> 02:27:32.250
This has come up
time and time again,

02:27:32.250 --> 02:27:34.370
I mean Roger said
the same thing,

02:27:34.370 --> 02:27:37.120
looking at the British
building industry.

02:27:37.120 --> 02:27:40.370
There's always going to be
competing higher priorities

02:27:40.370 --> 02:27:43.120
than tying everything up
very nicely with a bow

02:27:43.120 --> 02:27:44.900
at the end of a project.

02:27:44.900 --> 02:27:48.200
So really it has to come back
to things like deliverables,

02:27:48.200 --> 02:27:54.220
like externally imposed
requirements.

02:27:54.220 --> 02:27:58.310
If we, as Greg said, if the
standards are not only asked

02:27:58.310 --> 02:28:01.800
for by clients, by Governments,
by regulatory agencies,

02:28:01.800 --> 02:28:06.850
but also tested and verified
then they will happen.

02:28:06.850 --> 02:28:11.660
I thought it particularly
interesting comment

02:28:11.660 --> 02:28:14.730
from that first session,
too, a couple things.

02:28:14.730 --> 02:28:19.160
One, still on standards,
Greg's comment

02:28:19.160 --> 02:28:20.810
that we don't have standards
about how you get there,

02:28:20.810 --> 02:28:23.390
just what ends up being
delivered is really fascinating

02:28:23.390 --> 02:28:25.180
and I think ties into a
lot of the other comments

02:28:25.180 --> 02:28:27.540
that we've heard about the need

02:28:27.540 --> 02:28:32.090
for say submitting
narratives along with files

02:28:32.090 --> 02:28:33.530
or documenting workflows.

02:28:33.530 --> 02:28:38.010
This idea that like, especially
in the architectural realm,

02:28:38.010 --> 02:28:41.300
especially with smaller
firms every project is going

02:28:41.300 --> 02:28:46.000
to have its own workflow and its
own needs and its own software,

02:28:46.000 --> 02:28:48.700
unless there's some
reason not to.

02:28:48.700 --> 02:28:51.540
But maybe that's okay, it's just
that when it gets ultimately

02:28:51.540 --> 02:28:53.450
to other architects,
to architects

02:28:53.450 --> 02:28:56.270
at the same firm 20 years
later to deal with the assets,

02:28:56.270 --> 02:28:58.630
if it comes to a
place like CCA we have

02:28:58.630 --> 02:28:59.930
to know a little bit more.

02:28:59.930 --> 02:29:01.930
We can't just be
presented with the files.

02:29:01.930 --> 02:29:05.150
I think in our experience at
CCA doing the kind of thing

02:29:05.150 --> 02:29:09.840
that Balmori is doing with Yale
is a really great exercise.

02:29:09.840 --> 02:29:11.900
We've even sometimes
when we get the files

02:29:11.900 --> 02:29:14.580
in basically set-up a
Skype call with the people

02:29:14.580 --> 02:29:16.260
who actually created them
and shared our screen

02:29:16.260 --> 02:29:17.660
and just walked through
the directories

02:29:17.660 --> 02:29:20.740
and like tell me a story about
this, the same way you might do

02:29:20.740 --> 02:29:22.590
in history by like
showing someone a photo

02:29:22.590 --> 02:29:23.890
to jog their memory.

02:29:23.890 --> 02:29:26.450
These kinds of things are
really, really important.

02:29:26.450 --> 02:29:31.420
I think we hear some consistent
things about labor and time,

02:29:31.420 --> 02:29:34.820
that firms often don't have a
person dedicated to arranging

02:29:34.820 --> 02:29:36.410
and scribing the data
or that it's sort

02:29:36.410 --> 02:29:38.890
of like a secondary
task at the end.

02:29:38.890 --> 02:29:41.530
That it tends to be either
the architects, themselves,

02:29:41.530 --> 02:29:44.380
sort of all pulling the
weight or technologists,

02:29:44.380 --> 02:29:46.580
who maybe have a
different perspective.

02:29:46.580 --> 02:29:50.420
My plug here would be if you
can afford it you should hire

02:29:50.420 --> 02:29:53.200
archivists because we
think about this a lot,

02:29:53.200 --> 02:29:55.960
but that's not realistic
for everyone.

02:29:55.960 --> 02:29:58.670
And like with collecting
institutions no individual firm

02:29:58.670 --> 02:30:00.640
or practice is going to solve
these things on their own,

02:30:00.640 --> 02:30:02.650
so all these initiatives
that we hear

02:30:02.650 --> 02:30:04.990
and they're very collaborative
I think are extremely important

02:30:04.990 --> 02:30:06.290
for a firm for moving
us forward.

02:30:06.290 --> 02:30:08.990
You know, things like
Lotar is a great example

02:30:08.990 --> 02:30:13.280
of basically different, actually
competing commercial entities

02:30:13.280 --> 02:30:15.870
recognizing that they
have common problems

02:30:15.870 --> 02:30:19.240
and cooperating together
demonstrating the business value

02:30:19.240 --> 02:30:22.380
and then actually being
able to implement standards

02:30:22.380 --> 02:30:24.690
to drive their cost
down, lower the number

02:30:24.690 --> 02:30:26.070
of mistakes being made,
all that sort of thing.

02:30:26.070 --> 02:30:33.460
And thinking about the creators.

02:30:33.460 --> 02:30:36.180
Also, something that's easy
to forget sometimes I think

02:30:36.180 --> 02:30:38.940
for us collecting
institutions who are faced

02:30:38.940 --> 02:30:42.690
by how daunting CAT and BIM
and 3 modeling files are

02:30:42.690 --> 02:30:44.440
that there's things
besides those

02:30:44.440 --> 02:30:45.820
that we need to be collecting.

02:30:45.820 --> 02:30:50.460
There's a whole realm of
documentation of knowledge

02:30:50.460 --> 02:30:53.840
about corporate culture,
about presices, about events

02:30:53.840 --> 02:30:57.840
that predated larger cultural
contexts that shine a light

02:30:57.840 --> 02:31:00.030
into why projects
happen as they were,

02:31:00.030 --> 02:31:02.830
why designs happened
as they were.

02:31:02.830 --> 02:31:06.270
And these things mean that
we're going to be receiving,

02:31:06.270 --> 02:31:08.240
thinking about collecting
institutions,

02:31:08.240 --> 02:31:14.660
not just an IFC model or not
just CAD files in whatever

02:31:14.660 --> 02:31:19.050
of the like 300 possible
formats they're in or whatever,

02:31:19.050 --> 02:31:20.730
but also we're going
to be receiving things

02:31:20.730 --> 02:31:23.660
like photo documentation
and video and e-mail

02:31:23.660 --> 02:31:26.150
and increasingly web
based collaborative

02:31:26.150 --> 02:31:29.040
like note platforms
and all kinds of stuff.

02:31:29.040 --> 02:31:32.580
And we need to be able
to address all of that,

02:31:32.580 --> 02:31:35.210
which means we can't focus all
of our efforts, time and money

02:31:35.210 --> 02:31:37.630
on like very selected pies.

02:31:37.630 --> 02:31:40.570
I think this also comes back to
collaboration, why this needs

02:31:40.570 --> 02:31:41.870
to be a collaborative effort

02:31:41.870 --> 02:31:43.950
because there are other people
working in those spaces.

02:31:43.950 --> 02:31:48.890
And the Mellon Foundation funded
a really amazing task force

02:31:48.890 --> 02:31:51.970
on e-mail archiving, sort of a
state-of-the-art of where we are

02:31:51.970 --> 02:31:54.310
with people from a bunch of
major research institutions,

02:31:54.310 --> 02:31:56.750
but also others like Microsoft.

02:31:56.750 --> 02:31:59.810
And those sorts of things
can really drive us forward.

02:31:59.810 --> 02:32:03.350
We, in the ADEAC
realm like don't need

02:32:03.350 --> 02:32:04.650
to reinvent the wheel,

02:32:04.650 --> 02:32:05.950
we can plug into these
other communities

02:32:05.950 --> 02:32:09.360
and like provide our
unique perspective and gain

02:32:09.360 --> 02:32:12.090
from other work that's
happening in the field.

02:32:12.090 --> 02:32:19.710
And I think there's a little bit
of kind of careful reflection

02:32:19.710 --> 02:32:22.980
that we should do
around capturing things

02:32:22.980 --> 02:32:26.130
like Matthew called
it capturing culture,

02:32:26.130 --> 02:32:30.080
Dennis called it
capturing transactions.

02:32:30.080 --> 02:32:32.240
In the end often what
we're interested in,

02:32:32.240 --> 02:32:35.580
especially in sort of more
like research institutions,

02:32:35.580 --> 02:32:38.660
is not just the end built
product but how we got there,

02:32:38.660 --> 02:32:39.960
the theory, the practices.

02:32:39.960 --> 02:32:42.420
And for those sorts of things
capturing the cultural elements

02:32:42.420 --> 02:32:46.310
that come before are
especially important.

02:32:46.310 --> 02:32:51.130
If we sort of move on a little
bit to the second panel,

02:32:51.130 --> 02:32:54.030
researchers and scholars,
I loved the quote

02:32:54.030 --> 02:32:56.730
from Kurt's colleague, show
me the uses and I'll begin

02:32:56.730 --> 02:32:58.230
to understand the value.

02:32:58.230 --> 02:33:01.140
Unfortunately, I don't remember
your colleague's name, Kurt,

02:33:01.140 --> 02:33:03.740
but that's really great
and I'm really glad

02:33:03.740 --> 02:33:05.290
that we had that session today.

02:33:05.290 --> 02:33:07.160
Who did that, I think those
of you who are working

02:33:07.160 --> 02:33:10.470
with primary, digital primary
source materials are really sort

02:33:10.470 --> 02:33:12.220
of on the vanguard.

02:33:12.220 --> 02:33:15.500
In some ways there's not a
lot of scholarship out there

02:33:15.500 --> 02:33:19.060
that tells us how people
use these materials,

02:33:19.060 --> 02:33:22.210
which to me means
I would implore you

02:33:22.210 --> 02:33:25.430
to not just share the end
products of your research,

02:33:25.430 --> 02:33:27.120
not just like publisher exhibit,

02:33:27.120 --> 02:33:29.820
but to share the
process, how you go there.

02:33:29.820 --> 02:33:31.700
Like what your research
questions are,

02:33:31.700 --> 02:33:33.550
whether you were able to
actually do what you intended

02:33:33.550 --> 02:33:36.300
to do or had to change
because of not being able

02:33:36.300 --> 02:33:39.090
to find collections or
not being able to do

02:33:39.090 --> 02:33:40.790
with collections
what you wanted.

02:33:40.790 --> 02:33:42.850
For those of us who
manage these collections

02:33:42.850 --> 02:33:44.830
and provide the access to them
these are things that we need

02:33:44.830 --> 02:33:46.590
to know in order to
inform our practice

02:33:46.590 --> 02:33:49.790
and better serve you in the end.

02:33:49.790 --> 02:33:52.100
Another thing that really
struck me is that almost none

02:33:52.100 --> 02:33:53.850
of the use cases that
were presented today dealt

02:33:53.850 --> 02:33:56.130
with a specific singular
project.

02:33:56.130 --> 02:33:58.520
They differed a lot
from how sort

02:33:58.520 --> 02:34:02.160
of like traditional
architectural historiography

02:34:02.160 --> 02:34:03.900
often gets presented.

02:34:03.900 --> 02:34:06.890
Instead it was a lot about
large datasets, comparisons,

02:34:06.890 --> 02:34:09.660
design languages, typologies.

02:34:09.660 --> 02:34:12.870
I'm wondering if this is because
we now have the technology

02:34:12.870 --> 02:34:15.220
to enable these sorts of
researches, if there's something

02:34:15.220 --> 02:34:19.080
about this present moment,
or if this interest is going

02:34:19.080 --> 02:34:20.380
to continue over time?

02:34:20.380 --> 02:34:22.980
I suspect it's the latter,
but the kinds of work

02:34:22.980 --> 02:34:26.530
that Andrew is doing
are really innovative,

02:34:26.530 --> 02:34:29.900
could not have been predicted
probably 10 or 20 years ago

02:34:29.900 --> 02:34:33.210
by collecting institutions
who are ultimately responsible

02:34:33.210 --> 02:34:34.850
for a lot of these collections.

02:34:34.850 --> 02:34:37.460
And I think that's a thing
that we need to think about,

02:34:37.460 --> 02:34:40.950
that maybe we don't need
to over-engineer the ways

02:34:40.950 --> 02:34:42.590
that we provide access
or the ways

02:34:42.590 --> 02:34:44.230
that we describe
our collections.

02:34:44.230 --> 02:34:46.340
Maybe the primary
responsibility for us is

02:34:46.340 --> 02:34:50.230
to securely hold these
collections, provide access

02:34:50.230 --> 02:34:53.750
as we can, and then
respond to scholarship

02:34:53.750 --> 02:34:56.210
and to the actual use,
rather than our sort

02:34:56.210 --> 02:34:59.250
of preconceived notions of how
people might want to interact

02:34:59.250 --> 02:35:01.430
with this material over time.

02:35:01.430 --> 02:35:03.690
Another thing that really
struck me that's a question

02:35:03.690 --> 02:35:05.920
that I have no beginning
of an answer

02:35:05.920 --> 02:35:08.530
for is I thought there was
a really interesting back

02:35:08.530 --> 02:35:11.820
and forth between sort
of Matthew's question

02:35:11.820 --> 02:35:14.820
of like can we guess which
software created a file

02:35:14.820 --> 02:35:17.820
by the geometry of the
design, versus this idea

02:35:17.820 --> 02:35:19.890
of fully interoperable
data that's not tied

02:35:19.890 --> 02:35:21.590
to specific software platforms?

02:35:21.590 --> 02:35:23.170
I think there's probably
a lot to unpack there,

02:35:23.170 --> 02:35:31.700
I don't really know how, I'll
leave that to some of you.

02:35:31.700 --> 02:35:36.030
Yes, again, I'd implore you
basically tell us as much

02:35:36.030 --> 02:35:38.190
as you can about what you
are doing with this material

02:35:38.190 --> 02:35:39.530
and what you want to do.

02:35:39.530 --> 02:35:42.570
We will be bound sometimes
by other obligations,

02:35:42.570 --> 02:35:44.060
by our donor agreements
for instance.

02:35:44.060 --> 02:35:46.550
It's not so easy to
convince donors to give

02:35:46.550 --> 02:35:49.960
over 3D high fidelity
representations of buildings

02:35:49.960 --> 02:35:52.220
that could be used to
reconstruct it or basically are

02:35:52.220 --> 02:35:54.300
like a virtual analog
of a building.

02:35:54.300 --> 02:35:56.220
So there are other sort
of factors at play here,

02:35:56.220 --> 02:36:00.050
but I think we are, we will
largely be open to reflecting

02:36:00.050 --> 02:36:04.700
on our practices and seeing if
we actually are able to break

02:36:04.700 --> 02:36:06.390
with some of our older
practices, if we're able

02:36:06.390 --> 02:36:08.030
to provide freer
access, if we're able

02:36:08.030 --> 02:36:12.650
to better support new
research methodologies.

02:36:12.650 --> 02:36:17.860
A couple things for the
collecting institutions

02:36:17.860 --> 02:36:22.110
and maybe this is the part where
it might be a bit more of a call

02:36:22.110 --> 02:36:27.480
to action for me because this
is my world a little more.

02:36:27.480 --> 02:36:31.830
Like I said, let's not start
trying to go from A to Z

02:36:31.830 --> 02:36:34.350
and like over-engineering
our access solutions.

02:36:34.350 --> 02:36:40.480
From what I hear from Matthew,
from Andrew the collections

02:36:40.480 --> 02:36:44.550
that people need to support
scholarship largely are not

02:36:44.550 --> 02:36:46.590
in our collecting institutions,

02:36:46.590 --> 02:36:49.170
and to me that should
be our first priority,

02:36:49.170 --> 02:36:53.090
especially for these sort of
like these first few decades

02:36:53.090 --> 02:36:58.460
of digital design where largely
they were incidentally collected

02:36:58.460 --> 02:37:06.560
by collecting institutions and
won't be there for very long

02:37:06.560 --> 02:37:10.590
for us to collect,
either from people moving

02:37:10.590 --> 02:37:13.770
on to different projects,
retiring, the media degrading.

02:37:13.770 --> 02:37:16.860
I spend a lot of my days
getting data off of old media,

02:37:16.860 --> 02:37:19.350
it's all well past
its reliable lifespan,

02:37:19.350 --> 02:37:21.910
there is significant data
corruption in even the stuff

02:37:21.910 --> 02:37:26.310
from 10 years ago, 20 years
ago, so that's a real thing.

02:37:26.310 --> 02:37:31.010
I think it's really, we
need to think about this,

02:37:31.010 --> 02:37:33.420
these sort of new research
methodologies, like I said,

02:37:33.420 --> 02:37:36.120
machine learning and
machine vision, AI,

02:37:36.120 --> 02:37:38.440
thinking about that our
researchers may not necessarily

02:37:38.440 --> 02:37:40.970
want individual drawings,
they might want datasets

02:37:40.970 --> 02:37:42.440
and they might be
asking questions

02:37:42.440 --> 02:37:44.680
that are not interrogating
a specific architect

02:37:44.680 --> 02:37:47.120
or a specific archive but
a specific type of work

02:37:47.120 --> 02:37:51.130
that stretches across
archives and practitioners

02:37:51.130 --> 02:37:54.150
and whether we can actually
support discoverability

02:37:54.150 --> 02:37:57.490
to help people find the
material, like regardless

02:37:57.490 --> 02:38:00.290
of its provenance that meets
their research interests,

02:38:00.290 --> 02:38:03.220
is an interesting
question to me.

02:38:03.220 --> 02:38:06.230
One thing Matthew Allen
said that really struck me,

02:38:06.230 --> 02:38:07.560
that a collection of documents

02:38:07.560 --> 02:38:10.070
in their original order
provides a lot of clues.

02:38:10.070 --> 02:38:12.220
As an archivist that
sort of warmed my heart.

02:38:12.220 --> 02:38:14.520
I think it's true.

02:38:14.520 --> 02:38:16.640
[laughter] That's been
my experience, too,

02:38:16.640 --> 02:38:18.800
that with digital material
especially with all

02:38:18.800 --> 02:38:21.180
of the ex-wraps that you can
break if they're not bound in,

02:38:21.180 --> 02:38:22.690
all of these things,
often it's better

02:38:22.690 --> 02:38:25.190
to leave these collections
as they are and describe them

02:38:25.190 --> 02:38:27.470
as best you can and annotate
them with other kinds

02:38:27.470 --> 02:38:29.210
of information rather
than going in and trying

02:38:29.210 --> 02:38:31.800
to restructure them
and provide some sort

02:38:31.800 --> 02:38:36.230
of definitive hierarchical
binding style view

02:38:36.230 --> 02:38:37.970
into the material.

02:38:37.970 --> 02:38:43.040
And that we can maybe let
people be a little more hands-on

02:38:43.040 --> 02:38:44.860
and interactive with digital
archives than we could

02:38:44.860 --> 02:38:47.090
with physical, which is
something Matthew brought

02:38:47.090 --> 02:38:49.430
up as well.

02:38:49.430 --> 02:38:52.460
That, like Euan says, if our
access tools like emulation

02:38:52.460 --> 02:38:53.760
as a service allow us

02:38:53.760 --> 02:38:55.630
to basically spin-up a new
environment every time that's

02:38:55.630 --> 02:38:57.360
identical to the
original one regardless

02:38:57.360 --> 02:39:01.390
of what the person came before,
can we be a little freer,

02:39:01.390 --> 02:39:04.420
do we actually need to impose
so many restrictions that we had

02:39:04.420 --> 02:39:06.490
to largely based around
preservation concerns

02:39:06.490 --> 02:39:09.100
that aren't actually
that applicable to a lot

02:39:09.100 --> 02:39:10.400
of these new kinds of materials,

02:39:10.400 --> 02:39:13.060
I think is another
thing to ponder.

02:39:13.060 --> 02:39:14.720
Here's my call to action part.

02:39:14.720 --> 02:39:17.560
I think the biggest thing
holding us back as a community

02:39:17.560 --> 02:39:21.900
in this is not the difficulty,
not the size of the challenge,

02:39:21.900 --> 02:39:23.790
but the size of our capacity.

02:39:23.790 --> 02:39:26.780
That in the end of the day
before we can do any of the rest

02:39:26.780 --> 02:39:29.900
of the stuff we have to have the
files, we have to collect them,

02:39:29.900 --> 02:39:31.520
we have to preserve them.

02:39:31.520 --> 02:39:33.050
That means that libraries,
archives

02:39:33.050 --> 02:39:36.120
and museums need basic digital
preservation infrastructure,

02:39:36.120 --> 02:39:37.700
which is easier than
it used to be.

02:39:37.700 --> 02:39:40.710
There's a lot of really maturing
software out there, standards,

02:39:40.710 --> 02:39:43.300
professional communities.

02:39:43.300 --> 02:39:44.600
But at the end of
the day regardless

02:39:44.600 --> 02:39:46.960
of how you implement digital
preservation it does mean

02:39:46.960 --> 02:39:51.260
that you are going to have to
dedicate staffing and funding

02:39:51.260 --> 02:39:55.180
to it, which is as far
as I can see maybe one

02:39:55.180 --> 02:39:56.530
of the biggest obstacles

02:39:56.530 --> 02:39:58.880
to really moving
forward as a community.

02:39:58.880 --> 02:40:00.390
And we've been talking
about a lot of these issues

02:40:00.390 --> 02:40:06.550
for 20 years now and I think
we have a pretty good idea

02:40:06.550 --> 02:40:08.290
of what we need to
do at this point,

02:40:08.290 --> 02:40:10.320
we just need more
resources behind it.

02:40:10.320 --> 02:40:12.190
That's not all our fault,
though, because most

02:40:12.190 --> 02:40:13.820
of us don't have more
resources than we used

02:40:13.820 --> 02:40:16.780
to have even though we
have all these new types

02:40:16.780 --> 02:40:18.080
of assets to handle.

02:40:18.080 --> 02:40:21.170
So I think funding institutions,
too, should take this

02:40:21.170 --> 02:40:23.250
into consideration, but
ultimately it's probably going

02:40:23.250 --> 02:40:26.280
to require a lot of critical
evaluation of our services,

02:40:26.280 --> 02:40:29.120
where we spend our money.

02:40:29.120 --> 02:40:31.090
Maybe not everyone
needs to do it

02:40:31.090 --> 02:40:33.650
and probably not everyone needs
to do it and not everyone needs

02:40:33.650 --> 02:40:35.410
to collect at a large
scale, but if you want

02:40:35.410 --> 02:40:41.380
to it requires funding
and staffing ultimately.

02:40:41.380 --> 02:40:43.480
I think that said, we
don't have to start

02:40:43.480 --> 02:40:46.040
with the complete solution for
these things right off the bat.

02:40:46.040 --> 02:40:47.340
Things like the NDSA levels

02:40:47.340 --> 02:40:49.320
of digital preservation
are there to guide us.

02:40:49.320 --> 02:40:51.820
It's best to start at a level
where you know what you have,

02:40:51.820 --> 02:40:54.050
you know that you have backups,
you know that you can restore

02:40:54.050 --> 02:40:59.270
from those backups, and
then iterate up from there.

02:40:59.270 --> 02:41:01.540
There's a lot of education
and training out there.

02:41:01.540 --> 02:41:02.840
I think one of the things

02:41:02.840 --> 02:41:05.390
that didn't really get
addressed today all that much,

02:41:05.390 --> 02:41:08.550
except maybe obliquely through
some questions, is training

02:41:08.550 --> 02:41:11.920
and staffing around working with
these materials and archives,

02:41:11.920 --> 02:41:15.680
that suddenly we're expected
to have these competencies,

02:41:15.680 --> 02:41:19.740
that we understand archival,
we have archival expertise,

02:41:19.740 --> 02:41:21.900
we understand the sort
of architecture, design,

02:41:21.900 --> 02:41:23.960
engineering worlds,
we understand how

02:41:23.960 --> 02:41:26.520
to operate this CAD software
at least well enough to open

02:41:26.520 --> 02:41:29.340
up the files and look
around and say what they are

02:41:29.340 --> 02:41:30.890
and to describe them
to other people

02:41:30.890 --> 02:41:32.840
who probably have
more expertise than us

02:41:32.840 --> 02:41:34.940
in a way that's not invalid.

02:41:34.940 --> 02:41:39.720
Somehow we have to develop
a whole community of people

02:41:39.720 --> 02:41:41.870
like this and I think
we're getting there,

02:41:41.870 --> 02:41:44.230
but we can use some
critical self-reflection

02:41:44.230 --> 02:41:48.930
about how we set-up, how we
have training for current staff,

02:41:48.930 --> 02:41:50.300
how we encourage
a new generation

02:41:50.300 --> 02:41:51.810
of people to come into this.

02:41:51.810 --> 02:41:55.630
Things like the NDSR residency
program are fantastic,

02:41:55.630 --> 02:41:58.660
maybe we should think
about an NDSR architecture.

02:41:58.660 --> 02:42:01.310
I think there's a lot of
things that we could do

02:42:01.310 --> 02:42:03.550
as a community in there.

02:42:03.550 --> 02:42:05.270
Just like in aerospace

02:42:05.270 --> 02:42:09.500
and in the building community
we need to work together.

02:42:09.500 --> 02:42:12.250
We heard over and over and
over again today no one person

02:42:12.250 --> 02:42:15.380
or institution will solve
everything, we all are coming

02:42:15.380 --> 02:42:18.280
at this with different
expertise, different resources,

02:42:18.280 --> 02:42:22.810
different use cases, and the
more we work together the more

02:42:22.810 --> 02:42:25.420
we're going to work through
a lot of these issues.

02:42:25.420 --> 02:42:27.710
And in terms of practice,
like I said earlier,

02:42:27.710 --> 02:42:30.930
we can't really focus only
on CAD and BIM and models,

02:42:30.930 --> 02:42:33.910
we have to take a
larger picture approach.

02:42:33.910 --> 02:42:37.330
We have to think about how we
document culture and workflow

02:42:37.330 --> 02:42:41.070
and process and context
so that we don't just end

02:42:41.070 --> 02:42:43.670
up with some models that
are very extremely preserved

02:42:43.670 --> 02:42:45.750
in like perfect interoperable
file formats,

02:42:45.750 --> 02:42:48.670
but with no real
context for them.

02:42:48.670 --> 02:42:53.480
I think the last thing I'd say
for the collecting institutions,

02:42:53.480 --> 02:42:55.460
for my fellow people from
collecting institutions

02:42:55.460 --> 02:42:57.930
in the room, is it's
on us to demonstrate

02:42:57.930 --> 02:43:00.690
that our business case
exists and is viable.

02:43:00.690 --> 02:43:02.130
And we heard this
from the other types

02:43:02.130 --> 02:43:05.770
of stakeholders again today,
over and over and over,

02:43:05.770 --> 02:43:07.330
if you want people to
care about your problem,

02:43:07.330 --> 02:43:09.140
if you want to move forward
you have to demonstrate

02:43:09.140 --> 02:43:11.870
that it matters, why it matters
and that there's a way forward.

02:43:11.870 --> 02:43:14.710
And that's on us collectively.

02:43:16.240 --> 02:43:20.110
For the representatives of
software companies in the room

02:43:20.110 --> 02:43:22.610
or that might be watching
this at YouTube in the future,

02:43:22.610 --> 02:43:25.510
I think a few considerations.

02:43:25.510 --> 02:43:27.730
From architectural
and engineering firms,

02:43:27.730 --> 02:43:30.170
to facility managers, to
librarians and archivists,

02:43:30.170 --> 02:43:34.030
to Governments, we've heard
from a lot of people today

02:43:34.030 --> 02:43:36.310
that they are interested
in retaining access

02:43:36.310 --> 02:43:39.630
to files created in older
versions of your software.

02:43:39.630 --> 02:43:42.610
And maintaining compatibility
with old file formats

02:43:42.610 --> 02:43:45.610
and versions and ensuring that
your software can write files

02:43:45.610 --> 02:43:48.750
in preservation friendly openly
documented file formats have a

02:43:48.750 --> 02:43:50.190
real big role to impacts.

02:43:50.190 --> 02:43:53.090
There's been a lot of movement
on that front around BIM

02:43:53.090 --> 02:43:56.700
and IFC especially, which is
fantastic, but it's a thing

02:43:56.700 --> 02:43:58.630
that we can forget over time.

02:43:58.630 --> 02:43:59.930
And we live in a world now

02:43:59.930 --> 02:44:03.020
where even a W creative
cloud can't open the earliest

02:44:03.020 --> 02:44:05.890
Photoshop files and
Microsoft Word can't open

02:44:05.890 --> 02:44:09.890
up early Word files and those
are much simpler assets.

02:44:09.890 --> 02:44:13.950
So we have to think about
these things in terms

02:44:13.950 --> 02:44:15.790
of business value
clearly, but also in terms

02:44:15.790 --> 02:44:18.470
of their cultural
value and significance.

02:44:18.470 --> 02:44:22.830
As Euan demonstrated, there's
also quite a lot of us out there

02:44:22.830 --> 02:44:25.330
who are interested in running
older versions of the software

02:44:25.330 --> 02:44:28.070
in like virtual machines
and emulators,

02:44:28.070 --> 02:44:29.450
whether it's the
software vendors,

02:44:29.450 --> 02:44:32.250
whether it's software developers
who just think on their own.

02:44:32.250 --> 02:44:33.680
This is a really
interesting topic,

02:44:33.680 --> 02:44:36.020
whether it's institutions
thinking about applying

02:44:36.020 --> 02:44:38.920
for grants, we could use a
whole lot more development

02:44:38.920 --> 02:44:40.480
around these kinds of tools.

02:44:40.480 --> 02:44:42.900
What Euan has been able to do
and Klaus has been able to do

02:44:42.900 --> 02:44:44.370
and other people have
been able to do, you know,

02:44:44.370 --> 02:44:45.670
Rhizome for instance
applying this

02:44:45.670 --> 02:44:49.730
in the art world is amazing, but
it will only continue forward

02:44:49.730 --> 02:44:54.250
with kind of like funding and
support and given the promise,

02:44:54.250 --> 02:44:57.350
that's something we
should all think about.

02:44:57.350 --> 02:45:00.970
And, finally I think as a member

02:45:00.970 --> 02:45:03.990
of the Software Preservation
Network myself,

02:45:03.990 --> 02:45:07.270
I love that Jessica stressed
this, we need to acknowledge

02:45:07.270 --> 02:45:10.050
that software is infrastructure,
that it's a tool,

02:45:10.050 --> 02:45:11.360
that it's a way of
interacting with data,

02:45:11.360 --> 02:45:15.740
but also that it's our
cultural heritage and we need

02:45:15.740 --> 02:45:17.660
to think about that somehow.

02:45:17.660 --> 02:45:19.340
It's tough because there's
always business interests

02:45:19.340 --> 02:45:22.800
on the line and that's
completely understandable,

02:45:22.800 --> 02:45:27.840
but increasingly as the products
of our creative activities,

02:45:27.840 --> 02:45:31.280
commercial activities are
increasingly software dependent,

02:45:31.280 --> 02:45:33.090
bound now more and more online

02:45:33.090 --> 02:45:35.320
which only increases
these dependencies,

02:45:35.320 --> 02:45:39.360
I do think that there's a
valid argument to be made

02:45:39.360 --> 02:45:44.000
that there's a sort of
cultural element to this,

02:45:44.000 --> 02:45:45.710
a cultural obligation to this.

02:45:45.710 --> 02:45:47.070
I'm not the only one, you know,

02:45:47.070 --> 02:45:49.860
UNESCO has the Persist Project
that's recognizing the same

02:45:49.860 --> 02:45:53.510
exact thing on an
international level.

02:45:53.510 --> 02:45:56.220
For the standards
organizations in the room,

02:45:56.220 --> 02:45:58.650
you all are awesome,
keep doing that work.

02:45:58.650 --> 02:46:01.400
[laughter] Pushing for open
and documented standards.

02:46:01.400 --> 02:46:03.580
I found it very interesting
that the compatibility

02:46:03.580 --> 02:46:05.480
and adoption is increasingly
there,

02:46:05.480 --> 02:46:06.820
also that it's increasingly
there

02:46:06.820 --> 02:46:08.120
because Governmetns largely

02:46:08.120 --> 02:46:10.460
in Europe are increasingly
requiring it,

02:46:10.460 --> 02:46:11.960
which tells us a lot.

02:46:11.960 --> 02:46:15.250
For the clients and
Government agencies in the room,

02:46:15.250 --> 02:46:18.900
how we get things done and how
we ease our collective problems,

02:46:18.900 --> 02:46:23.860
you know, that the
power of regulation

02:46:23.860 --> 02:46:25.820
and deliverables
requirements is probably one

02:46:25.820 --> 02:46:27.200
of the biggest powers
in the space

02:46:27.200 --> 02:46:31.810
for making things happen came
up over and over and over.

02:46:31.810 --> 02:46:34.660
I'm also really glad
that we ended

02:46:34.660 --> 02:46:37.250
on two buildingSMART
presentations

02:46:37.250 --> 02:46:42.020
because I think it
outlines the kind

02:46:42.020 --> 02:46:43.530
of bright future
that's ahead of us.

02:46:43.530 --> 02:46:46.900
That, like Jessica said, we're
going to have to continue

02:46:46.900 --> 02:46:49.320
to deal with the old stuff and
that will require all kinds

02:46:49.320 --> 02:46:53.300
of creative solutions, it will
inevitably result in some loss,

02:46:53.300 --> 02:46:55.760
that's okay, that's the way
the world has always worked.

02:46:55.760 --> 02:46:58.890
But for the path ahead we
can at least try to lay

02:46:58.890 --> 02:47:01.970
down these standards,
encourage their adoption

02:47:01.970 --> 02:47:04.120
as much as possible.

02:47:04.120 --> 02:47:06.840
Again, for the collecting
institutions in the room,

02:47:06.840 --> 02:47:09.770
I think a lot of us archivists
and librarians have skills

02:47:09.770 --> 02:47:13.170
in terms of knowledge and
information organization

02:47:13.170 --> 02:47:15.620
and long-term preservation
that we're keeping

02:47:15.620 --> 02:47:17.500
within our professional
confines.

02:47:17.500 --> 02:47:20.880
It might behoove us to
think in a slightly more

02:47:20.880 --> 02:47:23.640
like post-custodial model,
like go to conferences

02:47:23.640 --> 02:47:26.900
that aren't library conferences,
go to meetings of architects

02:47:26.900 --> 02:47:28.410
and designers and
engineers and talk

02:47:28.410 --> 02:47:31.620
about why we organize
information the way that we do

02:47:31.620 --> 02:47:36.500
and try to make that
a back and forth.

02:47:36.500 --> 02:47:40.140
In general I think clearly
collaborative discussions

02:47:40.140 --> 02:47:44.400
and efforts are going to
be the key in all of this.

02:47:44.400 --> 02:47:47.690
And I thought I would, you know,
we all benefit from standards,

02:47:47.690 --> 02:47:49.690
we all benefit from
openly documented formats,

02:47:49.690 --> 02:47:52.720
we all benefit from
good documentation,

02:47:52.720 --> 02:47:55.820
from the firms themselves
who want to go back and look

02:47:55.820 --> 02:47:57.560
at materials, to scholars,

02:47:57.560 --> 02:48:01.430
to collecting institutions,
it's really everyone.

02:48:01.430 --> 02:48:03.170
And I thought I would leave this

02:48:03.170 --> 02:48:05.900
by just reiterating
Roger's comment,

02:48:05.900 --> 02:48:08.950
we have to invest upfront
to save in the end,

02:48:08.950 --> 02:48:11.490
which I think ultimately
underscores a lot

02:48:11.490 --> 02:48:12.790
of what happened here today.

02:48:12.790 --> 02:48:15.000
A lot of that investment
is happening already.

02:48:15.000 --> 02:48:17.290
It's clear, look at how
many people are in this room

02:48:17.290 --> 02:48:19.680
that are doing amazing
work on this problem

02:48:19.680 --> 02:48:20.980
from so many different angles,

02:48:20.980 --> 02:48:23.660
coming from so many different
stakeholder communities.

02:48:23.660 --> 02:48:27.180
It's fantastic, but it's up to
us to continue the good fight.

